"difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "In a nuclear physics laboratory, a researcher measures the mass of a ⁵⁶Fe nucleus to be 55.9207 u. Given that the mass of a proton is 1.00728 u and the mass of a neutron is 1.00866 u, and ⁵⁶Fe has Z = 26 and A = 56, the researcher wants to determine how tightly bound this nucleus is. What is the binding energy per nucleon of ⁵⁶Fe?", "explanation": "Step 1: Sum of nucleon masses = 26(1.00728) + 30(1.00866) = 26.18928 + 30.25980 = 56.44908 u.\nStep 2: Mass defect Δm = 56.44908 − 55.9207 = 0.52838 u.\nStep 3: Total binding energy = 0.52838 × 931.5 = 492.2 MeV.\nStep 4: BE per nucleon = 492.2/56 ≈ 8.79 MeV/nucleon.\nThis confirms that ⁵⁶Fe has one of the highest BE/A values, making it among the most stable nuclei.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["binding-energy-per-nucleon", "mass-defect", "iron-56", "numerical-problem", "scenario-based"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-nuclei-properties-20", "subtopic": "Nuclear Properties and Binding Energy", "topic_name": "Nuclear Properties and Binding Energy", "bloom_level": "evaluate", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "492.2 MeV/nucleon", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "0.528 MeV/nucleon", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "18.93 MeV/nucleon", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "8.79 MeV/nucleon", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "492.2 MeV is the total binding energy of the ⁵⁶Fe nucleus, not the binding energy per nucleon. Divide by A = 56 to get BE/A.", "misconception": "Forgetting to divide total binding energy by the number of nucleons"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "0.528 MeV/nucleon results from dividing the mass defect in atomic mass units by A without converting to MeV. Multiply Δm by 931.5 first.", "misconception": "Forgetting to apply the 931.5 MeV/u conversion factor"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "18.93 MeV/nucleon is approximately twice the correct value. Recheck arithmetic: 492.2/56 ≈ 8.79, not 18.93.", "misconception": "Arithmetic error in the division step"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-current-electricity", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "A potentiometer wire of length 100 cm has a potential drop of 1 V across it. The balancing length for a cell of EMF 0.4 V is:", "explanation": "The potential gradient k = V/L = 1/100 = 0.01 V/cm. For balance, E = kl, so l = E/k = 0.4/0.01 = 40 cm. At the balance point, the potential drop across length l equals the EMF of the cell, and no current is drawn from the cell being measured.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["potentiometer", "balancing-length", "potential-gradient", "EMF"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments-07", "subtopic": "Electrical Instruments", "topic_name": "Electrical Instruments", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "40 cm", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "60 cm", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "25 cm", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "4 cm", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "60 cm would correspond to an EMF of 0.6 V (60 × 0.01), not 0.4 V. The balancing length for 0.4 V is 40 cm.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "25 cm would correspond to an EMF of 0.25 V. For 0.4 V, l = 0.4/(1/100) = 40 cm.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "4 cm would result from using potential gradient as 0.1 V/cm instead of 0.01 V/cm. k = 1 V / 100 cm = 0.01 V/cm.", "misconception": "Error in calculating the potential gradient"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-current-electricity", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "A galvanometer of resistance 100 Ω gives full-scale deflection at a current of 2 mA. To convert it into an ammeter of range 0–2 A, the shunt resistance required is:", "explanation": "Shunt resistance S = IgG/(I - Ig) = (2 × 10⁻³ × 100)/(2 - 0.002) = 0.2/1.998 ≈ 0.1 Ω. Since I >> Ig, we can approximate S ≈ IgG/I = 0.2/2 = 0.1 Ω. The low shunt resistance ensures most of the current bypasses the galvanometer.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["galvanometer-to-ammeter", "shunt-resistance", "full-scale-deflection"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments-08", "subtopic": "Electrical Instruments", "topic_name": "Electrical Instruments", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "100 Ω", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "1 Ω", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "0.01 Ω", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "0.1 Ω", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "100 Ω equals the galvanometer resistance and would only divide the current equally. The shunt must be much smaller to carry nearly all of the 2 A.", "misconception": "Thinking shunt should equal galvanometer resistance"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "1 Ω would carry about 100/101 of the total current but is 10 times too large. S = 0.002 × 100/2 ≈ 0.1 Ω.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "0.01 Ω is too small. This would convert the galvanometer to a 20 A range ammeter, not 2 A.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-current-electricity", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "In a potentiometer experiment, two cells of EMF E₁ and E₂ give balancing lengths l₁ and l₂ respectively. The ratio E₁/E₂ is:", "explanation": "In a potentiometer, at the balance point, E = kl where k is the potential gradient (constant for a given setup). For cell 1: E₁ = kl₁, and for cell 2: E₂ = kl₂. Dividing: E₁/E₂ = l₁/l₂. This is the standard method for comparing EMFs using a potentiometer without drawing any current from the cells.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["potentiometer", "comparison-of-EMFs", "balancing-length"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments-09", "subtopic": "Electrical Instruments", "topic_name": "Electrical Instruments", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "l₂/l₁", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "l₁/l₂", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "(l₁ + l₂)/(l₁ − l₂)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "l₁ × l₂", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "l₂/l₁ = E₂/E₁, which is the inverse of what is asked. E₁/E₂ = l₁/l₂, not l₂/l₁.", "misconception": "Inverting the ratio"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "(l₁ + l₂)/(l₁ - l₂) is not the correct relation. The comparison formula is simply E₁/E₂ = l₁/l₂.", "misconception": "Confusing with sum-difference formulas used in other experiments"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "l₁ × l₂ is a product with units of cm², which cannot equal a dimensionless ratio like E₁/E₂.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-current-electricity", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "An ideal voltmeter has:", "explanation": "An ideal voltmeter should have infinite resistance so that when connected across a circuit element, it draws no current and does not disturb the circuit. This ensures that the voltmeter measures the true potential difference. In practice, voltmeters have very high but finite resistance.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["voltmeter", "ideal-instrument", "resistance", "measurement"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments-10", "subtopic": "Electrical Instruments", "topic_name": "Electrical Instruments", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Zero resistance", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Low resistance", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Infinite resistance", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "Resistance equal to the circuit resistance", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Zero resistance describes an ideal ammeter, not a voltmeter. A voltmeter with zero resistance would short-circuit the element.", "misconception": "Confusing ideal ammeter and voltmeter characteristics"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "Low resistance in a voltmeter would draw significant current, altering the circuit and giving an incorrect reading.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "If the voltmeter resistance equals the circuit resistance, it would draw as much current as the circuit element and significantly disturb the measurement.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-current-electricity", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "In a potentiometer experiment to measure the internal resistance of a cell, the balancing length without any external resistance is l₁ and with an external resistance R in the cell circuit it is l₂. The internal resistance of the cell is:", "explanation": "Without external resistance: E = kl₁. With external resistance R: V = kl₂, where V = ER/(R + r) is the terminal voltage. So E/V = l₁/l₂ = (R + r)/R. Solving: r = R(l₁ - l₂)/l₂. This method gives accurate results because the potentiometer draws no current at balance.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["potentiometer", "internal-resistance", "balancing-length", "cell"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments-11", "subtopic": "Electrical Instruments", "topic_name": "Electrical Instruments", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "R(l₁ − l₂)/l₂", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "R(l₁ − l₂)/l₁", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Rl₂/(l₁ − l₂)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "R(l₁ + l₂)/l₂", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "R(l₁ - l₂)/l₁ incorrectly places l₁ in the denominator. The correct derivation gives l₂ in the denominator: r = R(l₁/l₂ - 1) = R(l₁ - l₂)/l₂.", "misconception": "Swapping l₁ and l₂ in the denominator"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Rl₂/(l₁ - l₂) is the inverse of the correct expression. Since l₁/l₂ = (R + r)/R, solving for r gives r = R(l₁ - l₂)/l₂.", "misconception": "Inverting the expression during derivation"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "R(l₁ + l₂)/l₂ uses addition instead of subtraction. The correct formula involves l₁ - l₂ since l₁ > l₂ (EMF > terminal voltage).", "misconception": "Using addition instead of subtraction of balancing lengths"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-current-electricity", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "In a Wheatstone bridge, P = 100 Ω, Q = 1000 Ω, R = 40 Ω, and S = 400 Ω. If the galvanometer and battery are interchanged, the bridge will:", "explanation": "The balance condition P/Q = R/S gives 100/1000 = 1/10 and 40/400 = 1/10. Since P/Q = R/S, the bridge is balanced. Interchanging the galvanometer and battery does not affect the balance condition of a Wheatstone bridge. The balance depends only on the resistance ratios, which remain unchanged.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["wheatstone-bridge", "balanced-condition", "galvanometer-battery-interchange"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments-12", "subtopic": "Electrical Instruments", "topic_name": "Electrical Instruments", "bloom_level": "evaluate", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Become unbalanced", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Remain balanced", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "Show reduced sensitivity", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Require different resistance values for balance", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "The balance condition P/Q = R/S depends only on resistance values, not on the positions of galvanometer and battery. Interchanging them does not affect balance.", "misconception": "Thinking the balance depends on the position of the galvanometer"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "While sensitivity may change after interchange, the question asks about balance. The bridge remains balanced since P/Q = R/S still holds.", "misconception": "Confusing sensitivity with balance condition"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The balance condition is a property of the four resistances only. No different values are needed since P/Q = R/S = 1/10 remains true.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-current-electricity", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Assertion (A): A potentiometer is preferred over a voltmeter for measuring the EMF of a cell.\nReason (R): A potentiometer draws no current from the cell at the balance point.", "explanation": "Both statements are correct, and R is the correct explanation of A. A voltmeter draws a small current, so it measures terminal voltage (V = E - Ir), not true EMF. A potentiometer, at balance, draws zero current from the cell (null method), so it measures the true EMF. This zero-current condition makes the potentiometer ideal for EMF measurement.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["potentiometer", "voltmeter", "EMF-measurement", "null-method"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments-13", "subtopic": "Electrical Instruments", "topic_name": "Electrical Instruments", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "Drawing no current is exactly why the potentiometer gives true EMF (no Ir drop). This is a direct cause-and-effect, making R the correct explanation of A.", "misconception": "Not recognizing that zero current directly explains the accuracy of EMF measurement"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The reason is correct. At the balance point of a potentiometer, no current flows through the cell being tested, as the galvanometer reads zero.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The assertion is correct. Potentiometers give more accurate EMF readings than voltmeters because they use a null method.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-current-electricity", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Assertion (A): An ammeter is always connected in series with the circuit element through which current is to be measured.\nReason (R): An ammeter has very high resistance so that it does not alter the current in the circuit.", "explanation": "The assertion is correct: an ammeter must be connected in series so that the same current that flows through the element also flows through the ammeter. However, the reason is incorrect: an ammeter has very LOW resistance (ideally zero), not high resistance. If it had high resistance, it would significantly reduce the current being measured. The low resistance ensures minimal disturbance to the circuit.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["ammeter", "series-connection", "low-resistance", "measurement"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments-14", "subtopic": "Electrical Instruments", "topic_name": "Electrical Instruments", "bloom_level": "evaluate", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "The reason is factually wrong: an ammeter has very LOW resistance, not high resistance. Therefore, A and B are both eliminated.", "misconception": "Thinking ammeters have high resistance"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "Since the reason is incorrect (ammeter has low resistance, not high), this option is also wrong.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The assertion is correct. An ammeter must be in series to measure the current flowing through a component. Series connection ensures the same current passes through both.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-current-electricity", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Match the instruments (Column-I) with their key characteristics (Column-II):\n\nColumn-I:\nA. Ammeter\nB. Voltmeter\nC. Potentiometer\nD. Galvanometer\n\nColumn-II:\n1. Measures EMF accurately using null method\n2. Connected in series; has low resistance\n3. Detects small currents; shows deflection\n4. Connected in parallel; has high resistance", "explanation": "An ammeter is connected in series and has low resistance (A→2). A voltmeter is connected in parallel and has high resistance (B→4). A potentiometer uses the null method to measure EMF accurately (C→1). A galvanometer is a sensitive device that detects small currents (D→3).", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["ammeter", "voltmeter", "potentiometer", "galvanometer", "characteristics"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments-15", "subtopic": "Electrical Instruments", "topic_name": "Electrical Instruments", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A-4, B-2, C-1, D-3", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "A-2, B-4, C-3, D-1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A-1, B-3, C-4, D-2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A-2, B-4, C-1, D-3", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This assigns high resistance/parallel (4) to ammeter and low resistance/series (2) to voltmeter, which is exactly reversed.", "misconception": "Swapping ammeter and voltmeter properties"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "This assigns galvanometer to null method (1) and potentiometer to detecting small currents (3). The potentiometer uses the null method, not the galvanometer.", "misconception": "Confusing potentiometer and galvanometer functions"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This scrambles all matchings. Ammeter is connected in series (2), not null method (1).", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-current-electricity", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Match the following potentiometer applications (Column-I) with the relevant formula (Column-II):\n\nColumn-I:\nA. EMF of a cell\nB. Comparison of two EMFs\nC. Internal resistance of a cell\nD. Potential gradient of the wire\n\nColumn-II:\n1. k = V/L (V across wire, L is total length)\n2. E = kl (k = potential gradient, l = balancing length)\n3. r = R(l₁ − l₂)/l₂\n4. E₁/E₂ = l₁/l₂", "explanation": "EMF of a cell is found using E = kl (A→2). Comparison of EMFs uses E₁/E₂ = l₁/l₂ (B→4). Internal resistance of a cell is given by r = R(l₁ - l₂)/l₂ (C→3). Potential gradient is k = V/L (D→1). These are the fundamental formulas for all standard potentiometer experiments.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["potentiometer", "EMF", "internal-resistance", "potential-gradient", "comparison"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments-16", "subtopic": "Electrical Instruments", "topic_name": "Electrical Instruments", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A-1, B-4, C-3, D-2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "A-2, B-4, C-3, D-1", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "A-4, B-2, C-1, D-3", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A-3, B-1, C-2, D-4", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This assigns the potential gradient formula (k = V/L) to EMF measurement, but EMF is found using E = kl (2), not k = V/L (1).", "misconception": "Confusing the potential gradient formula with the EMF measurement formula"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This assigns E₁/E₂ = l₁/l₂ to EMF of a single cell, but that formula is for comparing two EMFs, not measuring one.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This completely scrambles the matchings, assigning the internal resistance formula to EMF measurement and vice versa.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-current-electricity", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "A metre bridge is a practical form of the Wheatstone bridge.", "explanation": "This statement is TRUE. A metre bridge (also called a slide-wire bridge) is a practical implementation of the Wheatstone bridge. It uses a 1-metre uniform resistance wire to form two arms of the bridge, and the jockey can be slid along the wire to find the balance point. The ratio of wire lengths gives the ratio of resistances.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["metre-bridge", "wheatstone-bridge", "practical-form"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments-17", "subtopic": "Electrical Instruments", "topic_name": "Electrical Instruments", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "A metre bridge is indeed a practical form of the Wheatstone bridge. It uses the same balance condition (P/Q = R/S) with a uniform wire replacing two resistance arms.", "misconception": "Not recognizing that the metre bridge is based on Wheatstone bridge principle"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This option is not applicable for this question type.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This option is not applicable for this question type.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-current-electricity", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "A voltmeter should be connected in series with the circuit element to measure the potential difference across it.", "explanation": "This statement is FALSE. A voltmeter must be connected in parallel (not series) with the circuit element across which the potential difference is to be measured. Parallel connection ensures the voltmeter measures the same potential difference as the element. If connected in series, it would measure something entirely different and disrupt the circuit.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["voltmeter", "parallel-connection", "measurement", "potential-difference"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments-18", "subtopic": "Electrical Instruments", "topic_name": "Electrical Instruments", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "A voltmeter is always connected in parallel, not series. Series connection is for an ammeter. A voltmeter in series would have very high resistance and nearly stop the current.", "misconception": "Confusing voltmeter (parallel) and ammeter (series) connections"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This option is not applicable for this question type.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This option is not applicable for this question type.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-current-electricity", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "fill-in-blanks", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The sensitivity of a potentiometer can be increased by _____ the length of the potentiometer wire.", "explanation": "The sensitivity of a potentiometer is increased by increasing the length of the wire. A longer wire means a smaller potential gradient (k = V/L), so a given EMF corresponds to a larger balancing length. This larger balancing length can be measured more precisely, improving the sensitivity of the measurement. Hence, longer wires allow detection of smaller differences in EMF.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["potentiometer", "sensitivity", "wire-length", "potential-gradient"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments-19", "subtopic": "Electrical Instruments", "topic_name": "Electrical Instruments", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Decreasing", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Halving", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Increasing", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "Not changing", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Decreasing the wire length increases the potential gradient, which reduces the balancing length and makes it harder to measure precisely, thus decreasing sensitivity.", "misconception": "Thinking shorter wire improves sensitivity"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "Halving the wire length would double the potential gradient and reduce sensitivity, not increase it.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "If the length is unchanged, the sensitivity remains the same. To improve sensitivity, the length must be increased.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-current-electricity", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "scenario-based", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "A student uses a metre bridge to find an unknown resistance X. She places a standard resistance of 10 Ω in the right gap and the unknown resistance X in the left gap. The balance point is obtained at the 33.3 cm mark from the left end. She then swaps the resistances (X in right gap, 10 Ω in left gap) and finds the new balance point.\n\nWhere will the new balance point be located?", "explanation": "First measurement: X/10 = 33.3/(100 - 33.3) = 33.3/66.7 ≈ 1/2, so X ≈ 5 Ω. When resistances are swapped: 10/5 = l/(100 - l), giving 2(100 - l) = l, so 200 = 3l, hence l = 66.7 cm from the left end. Swapping the resistances causes the balance point to shift to the complementary position (100 - 33.3 = 66.7 cm).", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["metre-bridge", "balance-point", "swapping-resistances", "unknown-resistance"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-current-instruments-20", "subtopic": "Electrical Instruments", "topic_name": "Electrical Instruments", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "33.3 cm from the left end", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "50 cm from the left end", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "25 cm from the left end", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "66.7 cm from the left end", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "33.3 cm was the original balance point. When resistances are swapped, the ratio inverts, and the balance point shifts to the complementary position at 66.7 cm.", "misconception": "Thinking swapping resistances does not change the balance point"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "50 cm would be the balance point only if both resistances were equal. Here X ≈ 5 Ω and R = 10 Ω, so they are unequal.", "misconception": "Assuming the balance point always moves to the midpoint"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "25 cm does not satisfy the balance condition for the swapped configuration. The new balance length = 100 - 33.3 = 66.7 cm.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "The de Broglie wavelength associated with a particle of mass m moving with velocity v is given by:", "explanation": "According to de Broglie''s hypothesis, every moving particle has an associated wave whose wavelength is given by λ = h/p = h/(mv), where h is Planck''s constant, m is the mass, and v is the velocity of the particle. This relation connects the wave and particle properties of matter.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["de-broglie-wavelength", "matter-waves", "wave-particle-duality"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie-01", "subtopic": "de Broglie Wavelength", "topic_name": "de Broglie Wavelength", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "h/(mv)", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "hv/m", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "mh/v", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "mv/h", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "This expression has dimensions of J·s·(m/s)/kg = m³/s², which is not the dimension of wavelength (m).", "misconception": "Incorrectly rearranging the de Broglie relation"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Dimensionally mh/v gives kg·J·s/(m/s) = kg²·m, which is not a length unit.", "misconception": "Confusing which quantities appear in numerator and denominator"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "mv/h is the reciprocal of the correct answer. The wavelength is inversely proportional to momentum, not directly proportional.", "misconception": "Inverting the de Broglie formula"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "In the Davisson-Germer experiment, the wave nature of electrons was confirmed by observing:", "explanation": "The Davisson-Germer experiment directed a beam of electrons at a nickel crystal and observed a strong diffraction peak at a specific angle. This electron diffraction pattern confirmed that electrons exhibit wave-like behaviour, as predicted by de Broglie''s hypothesis. The diffraction pattern could only be explained by treating electrons as waves.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["davisson-germer-experiment", "electron-diffraction", "wave-nature-of-electrons"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie-02", "subtopic": "de Broglie Wavelength", "topic_name": "de Broglie Wavelength", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Photoelectric emission from the nickel surface", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Interference of X-rays scattered by electrons", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Diffraction of electrons by a nickel crystal", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "Compton scattering of electrons", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Photoelectric emission demonstrates the particle nature of light, not the wave nature of electrons.", "misconception": "Confusing photoelectric effect with electron diffraction"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "The Davisson-Germer experiment used electrons, not X-rays, as the incident beam on the crystal.", "misconception": "Confusing electron diffraction with X-ray diffraction"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Compton scattering involves photons scattering off electrons and demonstrates the particle nature of electromagnetic radiation, not the wave nature of electrons.", "misconception": "Mixing up Compton effect with Davisson-Germer experiment"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "The de Broglie wavelength of an electron accelerated through a potential difference V (in volts) is approximately:", "explanation": "When an electron is accelerated through a potential difference V, its kinetic energy equals eV. Using λ = h/√(2meV) and substituting the values of h, m, and e, we get λ = 1.227/√V nm. This is a standard result frequently used in NEET problems involving electron de Broglie wavelength.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["de-broglie-wavelength", "accelerating-potential", "electron"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie-03", "subtopic": "de Broglie Wavelength", "topic_name": "de Broglie Wavelength", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "1.227/V nm", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "1.227/√V nm", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "1.227 × √V nm", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "1.227 × V nm", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "The wavelength depends on 1/√V, not 1/V, because kinetic energy is proportional to V and λ ∝ 1/√(KE).", "misconception": "Forgetting the square root in the relation between λ and V"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Wavelength decreases with increasing potential difference; this option suggests wavelength increases with V.", "misconception": "Inverting the relationship between λ and V"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This would mean wavelength increases with voltage, which contradicts the fact that higher voltage gives higher momentum and shorter wavelength.", "misconception": "Completely reversing the proportionality"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "Which of the following has the largest de Broglie wavelength if all are moving with the same velocity?", "explanation": "The de Broglie wavelength is given by λ = h/(mv). For the same velocity, the particle with the smallest mass will have the largest de Broglie wavelength. Among the given options, an electron has the smallest mass (9.1 × 10⁻³¹ kg), which is much less than a proton (1.67 × 10⁻²⁷ kg), a neutron (1.67 × 10⁻²⁷ kg), or an alpha particle (6.64 × 10⁻²⁷ kg). Hence the electron has the largest wavelength.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["de-broglie-wavelength", "mass-dependence", "comparison"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie-04", "subtopic": "de Broglie Wavelength", "topic_name": "de Broglie Wavelength", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Proton", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Neutron", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Alpha particle", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Electron", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "A proton has a mass about 1836 times that of an electron, giving it a much smaller wavelength at the same speed.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "A neutron has nearly the same mass as a proton and is much heavier than an electron.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "An alpha particle has a mass about 4 times that of a proton and roughly 7300 times that of an electron, so its wavelength is the smallest.", "misconception": "Thinking heavier particles have longer wavelengths"}]}}]'::jsonb, 'deploy-2026-03-05-b10');

SELECT insert_batch_questions('[{"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "An electron and a proton are accelerated through the same potential difference. The ratio of their de Broglie wavelengths (λ_e/λ_p) is:", "explanation": "When a charged particle is accelerated through potential difference V, its KE = qV. Since both electron and proton have the same charge magnitude, KE_e = KE_p = eV. Using λ = h/√(2mKE), the ratio λ_e/λ_p = √(m_p/m_e). Since m_p/m_e ≈ 1836, λ_e/λ_p = √1836 ≈ 42.8. The electron has a much larger wavelength because of its smaller mass.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["de-broglie-wavelength", "electron-proton-comparison", "accelerating-potential"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie-05", "subtopic": "de Broglie Wavelength", "topic_name": "de Broglie Wavelength", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "√(m_p/m_e)", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "√(m_e/m_p)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "m_p/m_e", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "m_e/m_p", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "This would give a ratio less than 1, meaning the electron has a shorter wavelength than the proton, which contradicts the fact that lighter particles have longer wavelengths at same KE.", "misconception": "Inverting the mass ratio in the wavelength formula"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The ratio involves the square root of the mass ratio because λ ∝ 1/√m at constant kinetic energy, not 1/m.", "misconception": "Forgetting the square root dependence"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This gives a very small number, implying the electron wavelength is negligible compared to the proton''s, which is the opposite of reality.", "misconception": "Confusing which mass goes in the numerator"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The de Broglie wavelength of an electron accelerated through a potential difference of 100 V is approximately:", "explanation": "Using the formula λ = 1.227/√V nm, where V = 100 V: λ = 1.227/√100 = 1.227/10 = 0.1227 nm ≈ 0.123 nm. This wavelength is comparable to inter-atomic distances, which is why electron beams can be diffracted by crystals.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["de-broglie-wavelength", "numerical-calculation", "accelerating-potential"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie-06", "subtopic": "de Broglie Wavelength", "topic_name": "de Broglie Wavelength", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "0.0123 nm", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "0.123 nm", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "1.23 nm", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "12.3 nm", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This corresponds to V = 10000 V. For V = 100 V, the wavelength is larger since λ ∝ 1/√V.", "misconception": "Using V instead of √V in the calculation"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This would correspond to V = 1 V. Check: 1.227/√1 = 1.227 nm ≈ 1.23 nm. For V = 100 V, the wavelength is 10 times smaller.", "misconception": "Not taking the square root of V"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This value is far too large for an electron accelerated through 100 V. Such a long wavelength would correspond to an extremely low voltage.", "misconception": "Order of magnitude error in calculation"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "If the kinetic energy of a particle is doubled, its de Broglie wavelength becomes:", "explanation": "The de Broglie wavelength is λ = h/√(2mKE). If KE is doubled, λ'' = h/√(2m × 2KE) = h/(√2 × √(2mKE)) = λ/√2. Therefore, the wavelength becomes 1/√2 times the original wavelength.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["de-broglie-wavelength", "kinetic-energy", "proportionality"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie-07", "subtopic": "de Broglie Wavelength", "topic_name": "de Broglie Wavelength", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Doubled", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Halved", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "1/√2 times", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "√2 times", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Wavelength is inversely related to momentum. Doubling KE increases momentum, so wavelength must decrease, not double.", "misconception": "Thinking wavelength is directly proportional to kinetic energy"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "Halving would require KE to be quadrupled, not doubled, since λ ∝ 1/√(KE).", "misconception": "Assuming λ ∝ 1/KE instead of λ ∝ 1/√(KE)"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This would mean wavelength increases when KE increases, contradicting the inverse relationship λ ∝ 1/√(KE).", "misconception": "Reversing the relationship between wavelength and kinetic energy"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The de Broglie wavelength associated with a gas molecule of mass m at temperature T is given by (k is Boltzmann constant):", "explanation": "For a gas molecule at temperature T, the average kinetic energy is (3/2)kT. Using the de Broglie relation λ = h/√(2mKE) = h/√(2m × (3/2)kT) = h/√(3mkT). This expression connects the thermal energy of gas molecules with their wave-like properties.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["de-broglie-wavelength", "thermal-wavelength", "kinetic-theory"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie-08", "subtopic": "de Broglie Wavelength", "topic_name": "de Broglie Wavelength", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "h/√(2mkT)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "h/√(mkT)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "h × √(3mkT)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "h/√(3mkT)", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This expression uses KE = kT instead of (3/2)kT. The factor of 3 in the denominator comes from using the correct average KE of a gas molecule.", "misconception": "Using KE = kT instead of (3/2)kT for average kinetic energy"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "This formula omits the factor of 3 from the average kinetic energy (3/2)kT and also misses the factor of 2 from the momentum-energy relation.", "misconception": "Incorrect substitution of kinetic energy in the de Broglie formula"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Planck''s constant must be divided by the square root term, not multiplied. Wavelength decreases with increasing temperature.", "misconception": "Inverting the de Broglie relation"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "In the Davisson-Germer experiment, the maximum intensity of diffracted electrons was observed at an accelerating voltage of 54 V and a scattering angle of 50°. The experimental de Broglie wavelength of the electron is closest to:", "explanation": "Using the formula λ = 1.227/√V nm: λ = 1.227/√54 = 1.227/7.35 ≈ 0.167 nm = 1.67 Å. This value agreed closely with the wavelength calculated from the Bragg diffraction condition using the known lattice spacing of nickel crystal (d = 0.91 Å), providing strong confirmation of de Broglie''s hypothesis.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["davisson-germer-experiment", "de-broglie-wavelength", "numerical-calculation"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie-09", "subtopic": "de Broglie Wavelength", "topic_name": "de Broglie Wavelength", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "0.567 Å", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "1.00 Å", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "1.67 Å", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "2.67 Å", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This value is too small. It would correspond to an accelerating voltage of about 467 V, not 54 V.", "misconception": "Calculation error in applying the formula"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "λ = 1.227/√54 ≈ 1.227/7.35 ≈ 0.167 nm = 1.67 Å, not 1.00 Å.", "misconception": "Rounding errors or incorrect square root calculation"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This would correspond to √V ≈ 4.6, i.e., V ≈ 21 V, which is not the 54 V used in the experiment.", "misconception": "Arithmetic error in division"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "An electron and a photon have the same de Broglie wavelength λ. If p_e and p_ph denote their momenta and E_e and E_ph denote their energies respectively, then which of the following is correct?", "explanation": "Since both have the same wavelength λ, their momenta are equal: p_e = p_ph = h/λ. For the electron, E_e = p²/(2m_e). For the photon, E_ph = pc = hc/λ. Since p_e = p_ph, but their energy-momentum relations differ (E = p²/2m for electron vs E = pc for photon), their energies are different. Specifically, E_e/E_ph = p/(2m_e c), which is less than 1 for typical wavelengths, so E_e < E_ph.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["photon-vs-matter-wave", "momentum", "energy-comparison"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie-10", "subtopic": "de Broglie Wavelength", "topic_name": "de Broglie Wavelength", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "p_e = p_ph but E_e ≠ E_ph", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "p_e ≠ p_ph but E_e = E_ph", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "p_e = p_ph and E_e = E_ph", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "p_e/p_ph = E_e/E_ph", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "Since both have the same wavelength, by p = h/λ their momenta must be equal. Their energies differ because the energy-momentum relation is different for massive and massless particles.", "misconception": "Thinking that same wavelength means same energy"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "While momenta are equal (both given by h/λ), the energy of an electron is p²/(2m) while that of a photon is pc. These are not the same.", "misconception": "Assuming identical wave properties imply identical particle properties"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Since p_e = p_ph, the ratio p_e/p_ph = 1. But E_e/E_ph = p/(2m_e c) ≠ 1 in general.", "misconception": "Assuming proportionality between momentum ratio and energy ratio"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "A proton and an alpha particle are accelerated through the same potential difference. The ratio of the de Broglie wavelengths associated with the proton to the alpha particle (λ_p/λ_α) is:", "explanation": "For a charged particle accelerated through potential difference V, KE = qV. So λ = h/√(2m·qV). For a proton: mass = m, charge = e. For an alpha particle: mass = 4m, charge = 2e. Therefore λ_p/λ_α = √(m_α × q_α)/(m_p × q_p)) = √((4m × 2e)/(m × e)) = √8 = 2√2.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["de-broglie-wavelength", "proton-alpha-comparison", "accelerating-potential"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie-11", "subtopic": "de Broglie Wavelength", "topic_name": "de Broglie Wavelength", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "1 : 2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "2 : 1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "1 : 2√2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "2√2 : 1", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This ignores the charge difference. The alpha particle has charge 2e and mass 4m. Both must be accounted for in the KE = qV relation.", "misconception": "Only considering mass ratio and ignoring charge"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "The ratio should account for both mass and charge differences. λ ∝ 1/√(mq), so the lighter particle with smaller charge has a longer wavelength.", "misconception": "Partially correct reasoning but missing charge factor"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This is the inverse of the correct ratio. The proton, being lighter and having smaller charge, has the longer wavelength.", "misconception": "Inverting the ratio"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "An electron microscope uses electrons accelerated through a potential of 10000 V. The resolving power of this microscope is high because the de Broglie wavelength of the electrons is approximately:", "explanation": "Using λ = 1.227/√V nm = 1.227/√10000 = 1.227/100 = 0.01227 nm ≈ 0.0123 nm = 0.123 Å. This wavelength is much smaller than that of visible light (400-700 nm), which is why electron microscopes can resolve much finer details than optical microscopes.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["electron-microscope", "de-broglie-wavelength", "resolving-power"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie-12", "subtopic": "de Broglie Wavelength", "topic_name": "de Broglie Wavelength", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "12.3 nm", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "1.23 nm", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "0.0123 nm", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "0.00123 nm", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "12.3 nm corresponds to V ≈ 0.01 V. For V = 10000 V, the wavelength is much smaller.", "misconception": "Forgetting to take the square root of V"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "1.23 nm corresponds to V ≈ 1 V. Check: 1.227/√1 = 1.227 nm ≈ 1.23 nm.", "misconception": "Using V = 1 instead of V = 10000"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This would correspond to V ≈ 10⁶ V, which is 100 times the given voltage.", "misconception": "Calculation error with powers of 10"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Assertion (A): The Davisson-Germer experiment provided direct experimental evidence for the wave nature of electrons.\nReason (R): In this experiment, electrons were diffracted by a nickel crystal, and the measured wavelength agreed with the de Broglie relation λ = h/(mv).", "explanation": "Both the Assertion and Reason are correct. The Davisson-Germer experiment demonstrated electron diffraction from a nickel crystal surface. The wavelength measured from the diffraction pattern (using Bragg''s law) agreed closely with the value predicted by the de Broglie relation, thus confirming the wave nature of electrons. The Reason correctly explains why the Assertion is true.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["davisson-germer-experiment", "wave-nature-of-electrons", "de-broglie-hypothesis"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie-13", "subtopic": "de Broglie Wavelength", "topic_name": "de Broglie Wavelength", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The reason directly explains the assertion — the diffraction of electrons and agreement with de Broglie''s formula is precisely what constituted the evidence for the wave nature of electrons.", "misconception": "Thinking the reason is unrelated to the assertion"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The reason accurately describes what happened in the Davisson-Germer experiment. Electrons were indeed diffracted by nickel crystal, and the wavelength matched de Broglie''s prediction.", "misconception": "Doubting the factual accuracy of the reason"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The assertion is historically and scientifically correct — the Davisson-Germer experiment is the landmark experiment that confirmed electron wave nature.", "misconception": "Questioning the significance of the Davisson-Germer experiment"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Assertion (A): A heavier particle always has a smaller de Broglie wavelength than a lighter particle.\nReason (R): The de Broglie wavelength is given by λ = h/p, where p is the momentum of the particle.", "explanation": "The Assertion is incorrect. A heavier particle does NOT always have a smaller de Broglie wavelength. The wavelength depends on momentum (p = mv), not mass alone. A heavy particle moving very slowly can have a smaller momentum (and hence larger wavelength) than a light particle moving very fast. The Reason is correct — λ = h/p is the de Broglie relation. However, since the Assertion is wrong, option D applies.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["de-broglie-wavelength", "momentum", "mass-velocity-dependence"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie-14", "subtopic": "de Broglie Wavelength", "topic_name": "de Broglie Wavelength", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "The assertion is not always true. A slow-moving heavy particle can have a larger wavelength than a fast-moving light particle. Wavelength depends on momentum, not mass alone.", "misconception": "Thinking wavelength depends only on mass"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "The assertion is incorrect. Consider a heavy particle at rest (λ → ∞) versus a fast-moving light particle (small λ). Mass alone does not determine wavelength.", "misconception": "Partially accepting an incorrect assertion"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The reason λ = h/p is the correct de Broglie relation. It is a fundamental formula in quantum mechanics.", "misconception": "Doubting the de Broglie formula"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Match Column I with Column II:\n\nColumn I:\n(P) de Broglie wavelength in terms of momentum\n(Q) de Broglie wavelength in terms of KE\n(R) de Broglie wavelength of electron (V in volts)\n(S) de Broglie wavelength in terms of temperature\n\nColumn II:\n(1) h/√(3mkT)\n(2) 1.227/√V nm\n(3) h/p\n(4) h/√(2mKE)", "explanation": "P → 3: The fundamental de Broglie relation is λ = h/p. Q → 4: Since p = √(2mKE), λ = h/√(2mKE). R → 2: Substituting electron mass and charge values, λ = 1.227/√V nm. S → 1: Using average KE = (3/2)kT, λ = h/√(3mkT). The correct matching is P-3, Q-4, R-2, S-1.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["de-broglie-wavelength", "formulas", "matching"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie-15", "subtopic": "de Broglie Wavelength", "topic_name": "de Broglie Wavelength", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "P-3, Q-1, R-2, S-4", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "P-3, Q-4, R-2, S-1", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "P-4, Q-3, R-1, S-2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "P-2, Q-4, R-3, S-1", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This incorrectly matches Q with the temperature formula and S with the KE formula. Q should match with h/√(2mKE) and S with h/√(3mkT).", "misconception": "Swapping kinetic energy and temperature formulae"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "P is the most basic form λ = h/p which matches (3), not (4). Also R is the electron-specific formula which matches (2), not (1).", "misconception": "Confusing the basic momentum formula with the KE formula"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "P matches the fundamental relation λ = h/p = (3), not the electron-specific formula (2). R is the electron-specific result matching (2), not (3).", "misconception": "Swapping the fundamental and electron-specific formulae"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Match Column I with Column II:\n\nColumn I:\n(P) Davisson-Germer experiment\n(Q) Heisenberg''s uncertainty principle\n(R) Electron microscope\n(S) Photoelectric effect\n\nColumn II:\n(1) Δx · Δp ≥ h/(4π)\n(2) Confirms wave nature of electrons experimentally\n(3) Uses small de Broglie wavelength of electrons for high resolution\n(4) Demonstrates particle nature of light", "explanation": "P → 2: The Davisson-Germer experiment confirmed the wave nature of electrons through electron diffraction by nickel crystal. Q → 1: Heisenberg''s uncertainty principle states Δx · Δp ≥ ℏ/2 = h/(4π). R → 3: Electron microscopes exploit the very small de Broglie wavelength of high-energy electrons to achieve resolution far superior to optical microscopes. S → 4: The photoelectric effect demonstrates the particle nature of light (photons).", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["davisson-germer-experiment", "uncertainty-principle", "electron-microscope", "photoelectric-effect"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie-16", "subtopic": "de Broglie Wavelength", "topic_name": "de Broglie Wavelength", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "P-2, Q-3, R-1, S-4", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "P-4, Q-1, R-3, S-2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "P-2, Q-1, R-3, S-4", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "P-3, Q-1, R-2, S-4", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This swaps Q and R. The uncertainty principle is Δx · Δp ≥ h/(4π), which is (1), not (3). The electron microscope uses small wavelengths for resolution, which is (3), not (1).", "misconception": "Confusing the uncertainty principle with the electron microscope principle"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "The Davisson-Germer experiment confirms wave nature of electrons (2), not particle nature of light (4). The photoelectric effect demonstrates particle nature of light.", "misconception": "Confusing wave nature of electrons with particle nature of light"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "P is about electron diffraction confirming wave nature (2), not about using small wavelength for resolution (3). R uses de Broglie wavelength for resolution (3), not confirming wave nature (2).", "misconception": "Swapping the Davisson-Germer experiment with the electron microscope"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "The de Broglie wavelength of a moving particle is inversely proportional to its momentum.", "explanation": "This statement is TRUE. According to the de Broglie relation, λ = h/p, the wavelength is inversely proportional to the momentum p. As the momentum of a particle increases, its associated de Broglie wavelength decreases. This is a direct consequence of de Broglie''s hypothesis connecting wave and particle properties.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["de-broglie-wavelength", "momentum", "inverse-proportionality"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie-17", "subtopic": "de Broglie Wavelength", "topic_name": "de Broglie Wavelength", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The de Broglie relation λ = h/p clearly shows that wavelength and momentum are inversely related. This is a fundamental and correct relationship.", "misconception": "Misunderstanding the de Broglie relation"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This option is not applicable.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This option is not applicable.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "The de Broglie wavelength of a cricket ball moving at 30 m/s is easily observable and measurable in daily life.", "explanation": "This statement is FALSE. For a cricket ball (mass ≈ 0.16 kg) moving at 30 m/s, λ = h/(mv) = 6.63 × 10⁻³⁴/(0.16 × 30) ≈ 1.38 × 10⁻³⁴ m. This is an incredibly small wavelength — far smaller than any known physical dimension — and is completely undetectable by any instrument. The wave nature of macroscopic objects is negligible, which is why wave-particle duality is only significant at the atomic and subatomic scale.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["de-broglie-wavelength", "macroscopic-objects", "wave-particle-duality"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie-18", "subtopic": "de Broglie Wavelength", "topic_name": "de Broglie Wavelength", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Calculate: λ = 6.63 × 10⁻³⁴/(0.16 × 30) ≈ 10⁻³⁴ m. This is about 10⁻¹⁹ times smaller than a proton. Such wavelengths cannot be observed.", "misconception": "Thinking wave nature is significant for macroscopic objects"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This option is not applicable.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This option is not applicable.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "fill-in-blanks", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "According to Heisenberg''s uncertainty principle, the product of the uncertainty in position (Δx) and the uncertainty in momentum (Δp) of a particle is always greater than or equal to _____.", "explanation": "Heisenberg''s uncertainty principle states that Δx · Δp ≥ ℏ/2 = h/(4π), where ℏ = h/(2π) is the reduced Planck constant. This means it is fundamentally impossible to simultaneously measure both the exact position and exact momentum of a particle. The product of their uncertainties has a lower bound of h/(4π) ≈ 5.27 × 10⁻³⁵ J·s.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["heisenberg-uncertainty-principle", "position", "momentum"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie-19", "subtopic": "de Broglie Wavelength", "topic_name": "de Broglie Wavelength", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "h/(2π)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "h/(4π)", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "h", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "h/(8π)", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "h/(2π) is ℏ (h-bar). The uncertainty principle states Δx · Δp ≥ ℏ/2, which equals h/(4π), not h/(2π).", "misconception": "Confusing ℏ with ℏ/2"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Using the full Planck constant h overestimates the minimum uncertainty product by a factor of 4π.", "misconception": "Omitting the 4π factor"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "h/(8π) is too small. The correct minimum is h/(4π) = ℏ/2.", "misconception": "Adding an extra factor of 2 in the denominator"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "scenario-based", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "A physics laboratory has an electron gun that can accelerate electrons through adjustable potential differences. A researcher needs to study the crystal structure of a sample with inter-atomic spacing of approximately 2.5 Å. For the electrons to be effectively diffracted by this crystal, the de Broglie wavelength of the electrons should be comparable to the inter-atomic spacing. The potential difference through which the electrons should be accelerated is approximately:", "explanation": "For effective diffraction, we need λ ≈ 2.5 Å = 0.25 nm. Using the formula λ = 1.227/√V nm: 0.25 = 1.227/√V, so √V = 1.227/0.25 = 4.908, hence V = (4.908)² ≈ 24.1 V ≈ 24 V. This demonstrates the practical application of the de Broglie wavelength concept — electrons accelerated through modest potential differences have wavelengths comparable to crystal lattice spacings, making them ideal probes for crystal structure analysis.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["de-broglie-wavelength", "electron-diffraction", "crystal-structure", "numerical-calculation"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-debroglie-20", "subtopic": "de Broglie Wavelength", "topic_name": "de Broglie Wavelength", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "2.4 V", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "54 V", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "100 V", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "24 V", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "At 2.4 V, λ = 1.227/√2.4 ≈ 0.79 nm = 7.9 Å, which is much larger than the required 2.5 Å.", "misconception": "Confusing V with √V in the formula"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "At 54 V, λ = 1.227/√54 ≈ 0.167 nm = 1.67 Å. This is too small compared to the required 2.5 Å spacing.", "misconception": "Remembering the Davisson-Germer voltage without calculating for the given spacing"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "At 100 V, λ = 1.227/√100 = 0.123 nm = 1.23 Å, which is about half the required wavelength.", "misconception": "Overestimating the required voltage"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "The photoelectric effect was first experimentally observed by:", "explanation": "Heinrich Hertz first observed the photoelectric effect in 1887 while working on electromagnetic waves. He noticed that ultraviolet light falling on a metallic surface facilitated the production of sparks. Later, Phillip Lenard studied the phenomenon in detail.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["photoelectric-effect", "hertz-observation", "history"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric-01", "subtopic": "Photoelectric Effect", "topic_name": "Photoelectric Effect", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Heinrich Hertz", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Albert Einstein", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Max Planck", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Phillip Lenard", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "Einstein provided the theoretical explanation of the photoelectric effect in 1905, but he did not first observe it experimentally.", "misconception": "Confusing the theoretical explanation with experimental discovery"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Max Planck proposed the quantum theory of radiation but did not discover the photoelectric effect.", "misconception": "Confusing Planck''s quantum hypothesis with photoelectric effect discovery"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Lenard performed detailed experiments on the photoelectric effect after Hertz''s initial observation, but he was not the first to observe it.", "misconception": "Confusing Lenard''s detailed study with the original observation"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The work function of a metal is 4.0 eV. What is the threshold frequency for photoelectric emission from this metal? (Given: h = 6.63 x 10⁻³⁴ J·s, 1 eV = 1.6 x 10⁻¹⁹ J)", "explanation": "The work function is related to the threshold frequency by φ = hν₀. Therefore, ν₀ = φ/h = (4.0 x 1.6 x 10⁻¹⁹)/(6.63 x 10⁻³⁴) = (6.4 x 10⁻¹⁹)/(6.63 x 10⁻³⁴) = 9.65 x 10¹⁴ Hz ≈ 9.7 x 10¹⁴ Hz.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["work-function", "threshold-frequency", "numerical"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric-02", "subtopic": "Photoelectric Effect", "topic_name": "Photoelectric Effect", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "4.8 x 10¹⁴ Hz", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "7.2 x 10¹⁴ Hz", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "9.7 x 10¹⁴ Hz", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "1.5 x 10¹⁵ Hz", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This value is roughly half the correct answer. Ensure you are correctly converting eV to joules: 4.0 eV = 4.0 x 1.6 x 10⁻¹⁹ J.", "misconception": "Using incorrect conversion factor for eV to joules"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "Check your arithmetic. The numerator should be 6.4 x 10⁻¹⁹ J divided by 6.63 x 10⁻³⁴ J·s.", "misconception": "Arithmetic error in division"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This is too high. Recheck: ν₀ = (6.4 x 10⁻¹⁹)/(6.63 x 10⁻³⁴) ≈ 9.7 x 10¹⁴ Hz, not 10¹⁵.", "misconception": "Error in handling powers of 10"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "In the photoelectric effect, increasing the intensity of incident light (above threshold frequency) causes:", "explanation": "When the frequency of incident light is above the threshold frequency, increasing the intensity increases the number of photons striking the surface per second. This increases the number of photoelectrons emitted per second, i.e., the photocurrent increases. However, the maximum kinetic energy of individual photoelectrons remains unchanged because it depends on the frequency, not the intensity.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["intensity", "photocurrent", "kinetic-energy", "photoelectric-effect"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric-03", "subtopic": "Photoelectric Effect", "topic_name": "Photoelectric Effect", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Increase in maximum kinetic energy of photoelectrons", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Increase in photocurrent but no change in maximum kinetic energy", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "Increase in both photocurrent and maximum kinetic energy", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "No change in photocurrent or kinetic energy", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Maximum kinetic energy depends on the frequency of incident light, not its intensity. Einstein''s equation: KE_max = hν − φ.", "misconception": "Believing intensity affects maximum kinetic energy"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "While photocurrent does increase with intensity, the maximum kinetic energy is independent of intensity and depends only on frequency.", "misconception": "Applying classical wave theory to photoelectric effect"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "More photons per second (higher intensity) means more photoelectrons per second, so photocurrent must increase.", "misconception": "Not understanding the relationship between intensity and photon number"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "The photoelectric effect supports the:", "explanation": "The photoelectric effect cannot be explained by the classical wave theory of light. It provides strong evidence for the particle (quantum) nature of light. Einstein explained it by treating light as composed of discrete packets of energy called photons, each with energy E = hν.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["particle-nature", "wave-theory", "photon-model", "quantum-theory"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric-04", "subtopic": "Photoelectric Effect", "topic_name": "Photoelectric Effect", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Wave nature of light", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Electromagnetic theory of light", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Transverse nature of light", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Quantum (particle) nature of light", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "The wave theory of light fails to explain the photoelectric effect, particularly the dependence of KE_max on frequency and the instantaneous nature of emission.", "misconception": "Confusing which experiments support wave vs particle nature"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "Maxwell''s electromagnetic theory predicts that energy of emitted electrons should depend on intensity, which contradicts experimental observations.", "misconception": "Confusing electromagnetic wave theory with quantum explanation"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The transverse nature of light is demonstrated by polarization experiments, not by the photoelectric effect.", "misconception": "Confusing different properties of light demonstrated by different experiments"}]}}]'::jsonb, 'deploy-2026-03-05-b10');

SELECT insert_batch_questions('[{"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Light of wavelength 400 nm falls on a metal surface with work function 2.0 eV. The maximum kinetic energy of the emitted photoelectrons is: (Given: h = 6.63 x 10⁻³⁴ J·s, c = 3 x 10⁸ m/s, 1 eV = 1.6 x 10⁻¹⁹ J)", "explanation": "Energy of incident photon: E = hc/λ = (6.63 x 10⁻³⁴ x 3 x 10⁸)/(400 x 10⁻⁹) = (19.89 x 10⁻²⁶)/(4 x 10⁻⁷) = 4.97 x 10⁻¹⁹ J = 4.97 x 10⁻¹⁹ / 1.6 x 10⁻¹⁹ = 3.1 eV. Using Einstein''s equation: KE_max = hν − φ = 3.1 − 2.0 = 1.1 eV.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["einstein-equation", "kinetic-energy", "wavelength", "work-function", "numerical"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric-05", "subtopic": "Photoelectric Effect", "topic_name": "Photoelectric Effect", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "1.1 eV", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "2.0 eV", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "3.1 eV", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "5.1 eV", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "2.0 eV is the work function itself, not the maximum kinetic energy. KE_max = photon energy − work function.", "misconception": "Confusing work function with kinetic energy"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "3.1 eV is the total energy of the incident photon. You must subtract the work function to get KE_max.", "misconception": "Forgetting to subtract the work function from photon energy"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "5.1 eV would result from adding the photon energy and work function instead of subtracting. KE_max = E − φ, not E + φ.", "misconception": "Adding work function instead of subtracting"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The stopping potential for photoelectrons emitted from a surface illuminated by light of wavelength 4000 Å is 1.2 V. What is the stopping potential when the wavelength is changed to 3000 Å? (Given: hc = 12400 eV·Å)", "explanation": "For λ₁ = 4000 Å: eV₀₁ = hc/λ₁ − φ. So φ = hc/λ₁ − eV₀₁ = 12400/4000 − 1.2 = 3.1 − 1.2 = 1.9 eV. For λ₂ = 3000 Å: eV₀₂ = hc/λ₂ − φ = 12400/3000 − 1.9 = 4.13 − 1.9 = 2.23 V ≈ 2.2 V.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["stopping-potential", "wavelength", "work-function", "einstein-equation", "numerical"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric-06", "subtopic": "Photoelectric Effect", "topic_name": "Photoelectric Effect", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "1.6 V", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "1.9 V", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "2.2 V", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "3.1 V", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This would imply the stopping potential scales linearly with the ratio of wavelengths, which is incorrect. You must first find the work function.", "misconception": "Assuming stopping potential is inversely proportional to wavelength without accounting for work function"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "1.9 eV is the work function of the metal, not the stopping potential for 3000 Å light.", "misconception": "Confusing work function with stopping potential"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "3.1 eV is the photon energy for 4000 Å light. For 3000 Å, photon energy is 4.13 eV, and you must subtract the work function.", "misconception": "Forgetting to subtract work function from photon energy"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "In the graph of stopping potential (V₀) versus frequency (ν) for the photoelectric effect, the slope of the line gives:", "explanation": "From Einstein''s equation: eV₀ = hν − φ, which can be rewritten as V₀ = (h/e)ν − φ/e. This is of the form y = mx + c, where the slope m = h/e. The slope is the ratio of Planck''s constant to the electronic charge, and is the same for all metals.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["stopping-potential", "frequency", "graph", "planck-constant", "electronic-charge"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric-07", "subtopic": "Photoelectric Effect", "topic_name": "Photoelectric Effect", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Planck''s constant (h)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "h/e (ratio of Planck''s constant to electronic charge)", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "Work function (φ)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Charge of electron (e)", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "The equation is V₀ = (h/e)ν − φ/e. The slope of V₀ vs ν is h/e, not h alone. If the y-axis were KE_max, then the slope would be h.", "misconception": "Confusing the V₀ vs ν graph with the KE_max vs ν graph"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The work function determines the y-intercept (−φ/e) and the x-intercept (threshold frequency), not the slope.", "misconception": "Confusing slope with intercept"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The electronic charge appears in the denominator of the slope (h/e), but is not the slope itself.", "misconception": "Incomplete analysis of the equation"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "The threshold wavelength for a metal surface is 5200 Å. The maximum kinetic energy of photoelectrons emitted when light of wavelength 3800 Å is incident on it is approximately: (Given: hc = 12400 eV·Å)", "explanation": "Work function φ = hc/λ₀ = 12400/5200 = 2.385 eV. Photon energy E = hc/λ = 12400/3800 = 3.263 eV. KE_max = E − φ = 3.263 − 2.385 = 0.878 eV ≈ 0.88 eV.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["threshold-wavelength", "work-function", "kinetic-energy", "einstein-equation", "numerical"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric-08", "subtopic": "Photoelectric Effect", "topic_name": "Photoelectric Effect", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "0.24 eV", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "0.53 eV", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "1.20 eV", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "0.88 eV", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This is too small. Recheck: KE_max = hc(1/λ − 1/λ₀) = 12400(1/3800 − 1/5200).", "misconception": "Arithmetic error in calculation"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "Verify your calculation. The photon energy is 12400/3800 = 3.26 eV and work function is 12400/5200 = 2.38 eV.", "misconception": "Computational error"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "1.20 eV is too large. Ensure you are correctly computing the difference of the two energy values.", "misconception": "Error in subtraction of photon energy and work function"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Which of the following observations about the photoelectric effect could NOT be explained by the classical wave theory of light?", "explanation": "The classical wave theory predicts that energy of a wave is proportional to its intensity, so increasing intensity should increase the kinetic energy of emitted electrons. However, experiments show that the maximum kinetic energy of photoelectrons depends on frequency, not intensity. This was a key failure of wave theory. Additionally, wave theory could not explain the instantaneous emission (no time lag) or the existence of a threshold frequency.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["wave-theory-failure", "frequency-dependence", "intensity-independence", "threshold-frequency"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric-09", "subtopic": "Photoelectric Effect", "topic_name": "Photoelectric Effect", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Maximum kinetic energy of photoelectrons is independent of intensity and depends only on frequency", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Light can transfer energy to matter", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Light is an electromagnetic wave", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Photocurrent increases with increase in intensity of light", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "Wave theory does predict energy transfer from light to matter. This is not the problematic observation.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The electromagnetic nature of light is a prediction of wave theory itself, so it does not contradict wave theory.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The dependence of photocurrent on intensity is actually consistent with wave theory, since more energy per second should release more electrons.", "misconception": "Thinking that the intensity-photocurrent relationship contradicts wave theory"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The momentum of a photon of wavelength 6600 Å is: (Given: h = 6.6 x 10⁻³⁴ J·s)", "explanation": "The momentum of a photon is given by p = h/λ. Here, λ = 6600 Å = 6600 x 10⁻¹⁰ m = 6.6 x 10⁻⁷ m. Therefore, p = 6.6 x 10⁻³⁴ / 6.6 x 10⁻⁷ = 1.0 x 10⁻²⁷ kg·m/s.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["photon-momentum", "wavelength", "de-broglie", "numerical"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric-10", "subtopic": "Photoelectric Effect", "topic_name": "Photoelectric Effect", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "1.0 x 10⁻²⁹ kg·m/s", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "1.0 x 10⁻²⁸ kg·m/s", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "1.0 x 10⁻²⁷ kg·m/s", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "1.0 x 10⁻²⁶ kg·m/s", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This is off by a factor of 100. Convert wavelength correctly: 6600 Å = 6.6 x 10⁻⁷ m, not 6.6 x 10⁻⁹ m.", "misconception": "Incorrect unit conversion from angstroms to metres"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "Check the exponent arithmetic: 10⁻³⁴ / 10⁻⁷ = 10⁻²⁷, not 10⁻²⁸.", "misconception": "Error in exponent subtraction"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This is 10 times too large. Verify: h/λ = 6.6 x 10⁻³⁴ / 6.6 x 10⁻⁷ = 10⁻²⁷.", "misconception": "Error in division of powers of 10"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "When light of frequency 2ν₀ is incident on a metal surface (threshold frequency ν₀), the maximum velocity of emitted photoelectrons is v₁. When the frequency is increased to 5ν₀, the maximum velocity becomes v₂. The ratio v₁ : v₂ is:", "explanation": "From Einstein''s equation: ½mv² = hν − hν₀. For frequency 2ν₀: ½mv₁² = h(2ν₀) − hν₀ = hν₀. For frequency 5ν₀: ½mv₂² = h(5ν₀) − hν₀ = 4hν₀. Dividing: v₁²/v₂² = hν₀/4hν₀ = 1/4. Therefore v₁/v₂ = 1/2, so v₁ : v₂ = 1 : 2.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["einstein-equation", "velocity-ratio", "threshold-frequency", "kinetic-energy"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric-11", "subtopic": "Photoelectric Effect", "topic_name": "Photoelectric Effect", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "1 : √2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "1 : 2", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "2 : 5", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "1 : √5", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "1 : √2 would mean the KE ratio is 1 : 2, but the actual KE ratio is hν₀ : 4hν₀ = 1 : 4.", "misconception": "Error in computing kinetic energy difference from threshold"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This ratio comes from assuming v is proportional to frequency, i.e., v ∝ ν. However, KE = h(ν − ν₀), so v² ∝ (ν − ν₀).", "misconception": "Assuming velocity is directly proportional to frequency"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This would give a KE ratio of 1 : 5, which would be the case only if the work function were zero.", "misconception": "Neglecting the work function in Einstein''s equation"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "In a photoelectric experiment, the graph of stopping potential (V₀) versus frequency (ν) for two metals A and B are straight lines as shown. If the work functions of A and B are φ_A and φ_B respectively, and threshold frequencies are ν_A and ν_B, then which of the following is correct? (Given that ν_A > ν_B)", "explanation": "In the V₀ vs ν graph, V₀ = (h/e)ν − φ/e. The slope h/e is the same for all metals (universal constant). If ν_A > ν_B, it means the x-intercept of A is to the right of B. Since the threshold frequency ν₀ = φ/h, a higher threshold frequency means a higher work function. Therefore φ_A > φ_B. The slopes are the same for both metals.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["stopping-potential-graph", "work-function", "threshold-frequency", "slope"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric-12", "subtopic": "Photoelectric Effect", "topic_name": "Photoelectric Effect", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "φ_A < φ_B and the slopes are different", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "φ_A > φ_B and the slope of A is greater than B", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "φ_A < φ_B and the slopes are equal", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "φ_A > φ_B and the slopes are equal", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Since ν_A > ν_B and φ = hν₀, a higher threshold frequency means a higher work function, so φ_A > φ_B.", "misconception": "Inverse relationship assumed between threshold frequency and work function"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "The slope of V₀ vs ν is h/e, which is a universal constant independent of the metal. Both lines have the same slope.", "misconception": "Thinking the slope of V₀ vs ν depends on the metal"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "While the slopes being equal is correct, φ_A > φ_B (not less) because ν_A > ν_B and φ = hν₀.", "misconception": "Incorrectly relating threshold frequency to work function"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Assertion (A): The photoelectric effect is an instantaneous process with no measurable time lag between incidence of light and emission of photoelectrons.\nReason (R): In the photon model, a single photon transfers its entire energy to a single electron in a single event.", "explanation": "Both the assertion and reason are correct, and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion. In the photon model, the energy transfer is a single quantum event where one photon interacts with one electron. The electron receives the photon''s entire energy at once, and if this energy exceeds the work function, the electron is emitted immediately (within about 10⁻⁹ s). This explains why there is no measurable time lag, unlike what wave theory would predict (where energy accumulates gradually).", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["instantaneous-emission", "photon-model", "time-lag", "wave-theory-failure"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric-13", "subtopic": "Photoelectric Effect", "topic_name": "Photoelectric Effect", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The reason directly explains the assertion. The instantaneous nature is a direct consequence of the one-photon-one-electron interaction described in R.", "misconception": "Failing to see the causal link between photon-electron interaction and instantaneous emission"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The reason is a correct statement of the photon model. A single photon does transfer all its energy to a single electron.", "misconception": "Doubting the validity of the photon model description"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The assertion is experimentally verified. Photoelectric emission occurs within 10⁻⁹ s of light incidence, which is essentially instantaneous.", "misconception": "Believing that photoelectric emission requires a time lag"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Assertion (A): When ultraviolet light is incident on a photosensitive material, the stopping potential increases linearly with the increase in frequency of incident radiation.\nReason (R): The maximum kinetic energy of photoelectrons is directly proportional to the frequency of incident radiation.", "explanation": "The assertion is correct: from eV₀ = hν − φ, the stopping potential V₀ = (h/e)ν − φ/e, which is a linear function of ν with a positive slope h/e. The reason states that KE_max is directly proportional to ν, which is incorrect. KE_max = hν − φ, which is a linear function of ν but not directly proportional (direct proportionality would require the y-intercept to be zero, i.e., φ = 0). Therefore A is correct but R is incorrect.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["stopping-potential", "frequency", "proportionality", "einstein-equation", "linear-relationship"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric-14", "subtopic": "Photoelectric Effect", "topic_name": "Photoelectric Effect", "bloom_level": "evaluate", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "The reason is incorrect. KE_max = hν − φ is a linear function but NOT directly proportional (proportional means passing through origin).", "misconception": "Confusing linear relationship with direct proportionality"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "The reason is factually incorrect because ''directly proportional'' implies KE_max ∝ ν (passes through origin), but the graph has a non-zero intercept (−φ).", "misconception": "Not distinguishing between linear dependence and direct proportionality"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The assertion is correct. V₀ = (h/e)ν − φ/e is indeed a linear function of ν, confirming that V₀ increases linearly with ν.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Match the physical quantities in Column I with their dependence in the photoelectric effect in Column II:\n\nColumn I:\nA. Maximum kinetic energy of photoelectrons\nB. Photocurrent (saturation)\nC. Stopping potential\nD. Threshold frequency\n\nColumn II:\n1. Depends on work function of metal only\n2. Depends on frequency of incident light and work function\n3. Depends on intensity of incident light\n4. Equals (h/e) times frequency minus (φ/e)", "explanation": "Maximum kinetic energy KE_max = hν − φ, which depends on frequency and work function (A-2). Saturation photocurrent depends on the number of photons incident per second, which is proportional to intensity (B-3). Stopping potential V₀ = (h/e)ν − φ/e (C-4). Threshold frequency ν₀ = φ/h depends only on the work function (D-1).", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["kinetic-energy", "photocurrent", "stopping-potential", "threshold-frequency", "work-function"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric-15", "subtopic": "Photoelectric Effect", "topic_name": "Photoelectric Effect", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A-3, B-2, C-4, D-1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "A-2, B-3, C-4, D-1", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "A-4, B-3, C-2, D-1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A-2, B-1, C-3, D-4", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "A-3 is wrong. Maximum kinetic energy does not depend on intensity; it depends on frequency and work function.", "misconception": "Thinking KE_max depends on intensity (classical wave theory error)"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "A-4 describes stopping potential (V₀ = (h/e)ν − φ/e), not KE_max. KE_max = hν − φ matches description 2.", "misconception": "Confusing the expressions for KE_max and stopping potential"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "B-1 is wrong. Photocurrent depends on intensity (number of photons), not just the work function. C-3 is also wrong; stopping potential does not depend on intensity.", "misconception": "Interchanging the dependencies of photocurrent and stopping potential"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Match the experimental observation in Column I with the correct explanation in Column II:\n\nColumn I:\nA. No photoelectric emission below threshold frequency\nB. Photoelectric emission is instantaneous\nC. KE_max is independent of intensity\nD. Photocurrent is proportional to intensity\n\nColumn II:\n1. Each photon interacts with one electron; energy transfer is a single quantum event\n2. One photon can eject at most one electron; more photons per second means more electrons\n3. Photon energy (hν) must be at least equal to the work function\n4. KE_max = hν − φ does not contain intensity; it depends only on ν and φ", "explanation": "No emission below threshold frequency occurs because the photon energy must equal or exceed the work function (A-3). Instantaneous emission is because each photon transfers its energy in a single quantum event (B-1). KE_max is independent of intensity because Einstein''s equation KE_max = hν − φ has no intensity term (C-4). Photocurrent is proportional to intensity because more photons per second yield more ejected electrons (D-2).", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["threshold-frequency", "instantaneous-emission", "intensity-independence", "photocurrent", "photon-model"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric-16", "subtopic": "Photoelectric Effect", "topic_name": "Photoelectric Effect", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A-3, B-1, C-4, D-2", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "A-1, B-3, C-4, D-2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A-3, B-2, C-1, D-4", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A-4, B-1, C-3, D-2", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "A-1 is wrong. The single quantum event (1) explains instantaneous emission, not the threshold condition. The threshold condition requires photon energy ≥ work function (3).", "misconception": "Confusing the explanation for threshold frequency with that for instantaneous emission"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "B-2 is wrong. The statement about more photons meaning more electrons (2) explains photocurrent proportionality, not instantaneous emission. B should match with 1.", "misconception": "Confusing photon-number argument with single-event energy transfer argument"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "A-4 is wrong. The absence of intensity in Einstein''s equation (4) explains why KE_max is intensity-independent, not why there is a threshold frequency.", "misconception": "Misassigning the intensity-independence explanation to the threshold condition"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "The energy of a photon is given by E = hν, where h is Planck''s constant and ν is the frequency of the radiation.", "explanation": "This is a true statement. The energy of a photon is given by Planck-Einstein relation E = hν, where h = 6.63 x 10⁻³⁴ J·s is Planck''s constant and ν is the frequency of the electromagnetic radiation. This is one of the fundamental equations of quantum physics.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["photon-energy", "planck-constant", "frequency", "quantum-theory"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric-17", "subtopic": "Photoelectric Effect", "topic_name": "Photoelectric Effect", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "E = hν is the correct Planck-Einstein relation for the energy of a photon. This is a fundamental equation in quantum physics.", "misconception": "Doubting the basic Planck-Einstein relation"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This is a placeholder option and not a valid choice.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This is a placeholder option and not a valid choice.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "In the photoelectric effect, the maximum kinetic energy of emitted photoelectrons increases with increase in the intensity of incident light (keeping frequency constant).", "explanation": "This statement is false. The maximum kinetic energy of emitted photoelectrons depends only on the frequency of the incident light and the work function of the metal (KE_max = hν − φ). Increasing the intensity at constant frequency increases the number of photoelectrons emitted per second (photocurrent), but does not change the maximum kinetic energy of individual photoelectrons.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["intensity", "kinetic-energy", "frequency", "photoelectric-effect"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric-18", "subtopic": "Photoelectric Effect", "topic_name": "Photoelectric Effect", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This is the prediction of classical wave theory, which was shown to be incorrect. KE_max depends on frequency, not intensity.", "misconception": "Applying classical wave theory prediction to the photoelectric effect"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This is a placeholder option and not a valid choice.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This is a placeholder option and not a valid choice.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "fill-in-blanks", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "A photon of energy 4.25 eV is incident on a metal surface having work function 3.75 eV. The stopping potential for the most energetic photoelectrons is _____ V.", "explanation": "Using Einstein''s photoelectric equation: eV₀ = hν − φ. Here, photon energy hν = 4.25 eV and work function φ = 3.75 eV. Therefore, eV₀ = 4.25 − 3.75 = 0.50 eV. Since eV₀ is in eV and V₀ is in volts, V₀ = 0.50 V.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["stopping-potential", "einstein-equation", "work-function", "numerical"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric-19", "subtopic": "Photoelectric Effect", "topic_name": "Photoelectric Effect", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "0.25", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "0.50", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "3.75", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "4.25", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "0.25 V is not the correct difference. V₀ = (4.25 − 3.75)/e = 0.50 V.", "misconception": "Arithmetic error in subtraction"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "3.75 V is the work function expressed in eV. The stopping potential is the excess energy above the work function, not the work function itself.", "misconception": "Confusing work function with stopping potential"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "4.25 is the total photon energy in eV. The stopping potential corresponds to the kinetic energy, which is the photon energy minus the work function.", "misconception": "Using total photon energy as stopping potential without subtracting work function"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-dual-nature", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "scenario-based", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "In a laboratory experiment, a student illuminates a clean caesium surface (φ = 2.14 eV) with monochromatic light from a mercury lamp. She measures the photocurrent using a sensitive ammeter and applies a retarding potential using a variable voltage source. When the wavelength of light used is 4358 Å, the photocurrent drops to zero at a certain retarding potential.\n\nWhat is the stopping potential measured by the student? (Given: hc = 12400 eV·Å)", "explanation": "Energy of incident photon: E = hc/λ = 12400/4358 = 2.846 eV. Using Einstein''s equation: eV₀ = E − φ = 2.846 − 2.14 = 0.706 eV. Therefore, the stopping potential V₀ ≈ 0.71 V.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["stopping-potential", "caesium", "mercury-lamp", "einstein-equation", "numerical", "scenario"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-dual-photoelectric-20", "subtopic": "Photoelectric Effect", "topic_name": "Photoelectric Effect", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "0.35 V", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "1.14 V", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "2.14 V", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "0.71 V", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "0.35 V is approximately half the correct value. Recheck: E = 12400/4358 = 2.846 eV, then V₀ = 2.846 − 2.14 = 0.71 V.", "misconception": "Arithmetic error in computing photon energy or the difference"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "1.14 V does not correspond to the correct calculation. Ensure you are using λ = 4358 Å and φ = 2.14 eV correctly.", "misconception": "Using incorrect wavelength or work function value"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "2.14 V equals the work function in eV. The stopping potential is the photon energy minus the work function, not the work function itself.", "misconception": "Confusing work function with stopping potential"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "In a half-wave rectifier, the output frequency is equal to:", "explanation": "In a half-wave rectifier, only one half (positive or negative) of the input AC signal passes through the diode per cycle. Therefore, for each complete cycle of the input, there is one pulse in the output. The output frequency equals the input frequency. If the input AC has frequency f, the output also has frequency f.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["half-wave-rectifier", "output-frequency", "rectification"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode-01", "subtopic": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "topic_name": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "The input frequency f", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Twice the input frequency (2f)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Half the input frequency (f/2)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Zero (pure DC)", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "An output frequency of 2f occurs in a full-wave rectifier, not a half-wave rectifier. In a full-wave rectifier both halves of the cycle produce output pulses.", "misconception": "Confusing half-wave rectifier output frequency with that of a full-wave rectifier"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Half the input frequency would mean one output pulse every two input cycles, which does not happen. Each input cycle produces exactly one output pulse.", "misconception": "Incorrectly halving the frequency for a half-wave rectifier"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The output of a rectifier is pulsating DC, not pure DC. It still has a ripple at a definite frequency. Only after ideal filtering does it approach pure DC.", "misconception": "Confusing pulsating DC with pure DC"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "A Zener diode is primarily used as:", "explanation": "A Zener diode is specifically designed to operate in the reverse breakdown region at a well-defined voltage called the Zener voltage. When reverse biased beyond this voltage, it maintains an almost constant voltage across its terminals regardless of current variations. This property makes it ideal for voltage regulation in electronic circuits.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["zener-diode", "voltage-regulation", "reverse-breakdown"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode-02", "subtopic": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "topic_name": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "An amplifier", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "A voltage regulator", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "A current amplifier", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A rectifier in power supplies", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Amplification requires active devices like transistors that can provide power gain. A Zener diode is a two-terminal passive device used for voltage stabilisation, not amplification.", "misconception": "Confusing voltage regulation with amplification"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Current amplification is a property of transistors (defined by current gain beta). A Zener diode regulates voltage, not current.", "misconception": "Attributing transistor properties to a diode"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Ordinary p-n junction diodes are used as rectifiers. A Zener diode is specially designed for the reverse breakdown region to regulate voltage, not for rectification.", "misconception": "Confusing the function of a Zener diode with that of a rectifier diode"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "In a full-wave rectifier using two diodes with a centre-tapped transformer, if the input AC frequency is 50 Hz, the ripple frequency of the output is:", "explanation": "In a full-wave rectifier, both halves of the AC input cycle are rectified. During the positive half-cycle, one diode conducts, and during the negative half-cycle, the other diode conducts. This produces two output pulses for every one complete input cycle. Therefore, the ripple frequency is twice the input frequency: 2 x 50 = 100 Hz.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["full-wave-rectifier", "ripple-frequency", "centre-tapped-transformer"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode-03", "subtopic": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "topic_name": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "25 Hz", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "50 Hz", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "100 Hz", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "200 Hz", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "25 Hz is half the input frequency. The ripple frequency in a full-wave rectifier is always greater than the input frequency, not less.", "misconception": "Incorrectly halving the frequency instead of doubling it"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "50 Hz is the ripple frequency for a half-wave rectifier (same as input frequency). A full-wave rectifier produces two pulses per cycle, so the ripple frequency is doubled.", "misconception": "Confusing half-wave and full-wave rectifier output frequencies"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "200 Hz would be four times the input frequency. A full-wave rectifier produces exactly two output pulses per input cycle, giving 2f = 100 Hz.", "misconception": "Incorrectly multiplying the frequency by a factor of 4"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "An LED (Light Emitting Diode) emits light when it is:", "explanation": "An LED emits light when it is forward biased. Under forward bias, electrons from the n-side and holes from the p-side are injected across the junction. When these minority carriers recombine with majority carriers, the energy is released in the form of photons (light). The wavelength (colour) of light depends on the band gap of the semiconductor material used.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["LED", "forward-bias", "recombination", "photon-emission"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode-04", "subtopic": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "topic_name": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Reverse biased", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Unbiased", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "At breakdown voltage", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Forward biased", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Under reverse bias, the depletion region widens and very little current flows. Reverse bias is used for photodiodes, not LEDs. LEDs require forward bias for electron-hole recombination.", "misconception": "Confusing LED operation with photodiode operation"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "In the unbiased condition, there is no net current flow and hence no significant carrier injection or recombination. Light emission requires carrier recombination driven by forward current.", "misconception": "Thinking that a diode can emit light without external bias"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Breakdown voltage applies to reverse-biased operation (as in Zener diodes). Operating an LED at breakdown would likely damage it, and the mechanism is entirely different from light emission.", "misconception": "Confusing Zener breakdown operation with LED light emission"}]}}]'::jsonb, 'deploy-2026-03-05-b10');

SELECT insert_batch_questions('[{"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "A photodiode is operated under reverse bias because:", "explanation": "When a photodiode is reverse biased, the depletion region is widened. This is advantageous because light-generated electron-hole pairs in the depletion region are quickly swept to opposite sides by the strong electric field, producing a measurable photocurrent. The wide depletion region also increases the volume where photon absorption can contribute to the current, and the fast carrier sweep leads to a quick response time. The reverse bias ensures that even a small change in light intensity produces a detectable change in current.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["photodiode", "reverse-bias", "depletion-region", "photocurrent"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode-05", "subtopic": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "topic_name": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "It increases the forward current significantly", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "It narrows the depletion layer for better absorption", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "It causes the diode to emit light", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "It widens the depletion layer, increasing the sensitivity to light and making the change in current easily measurable", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Reverse bias does not increase forward current. In reverse bias, only a small reverse saturation current flows, which changes with light intensity. This is the detection mechanism.", "misconception": "Confusing forward and reverse bias current behaviour"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "Reverse bias widens (not narrows) the depletion layer. A wider depletion region exposes a larger volume to incident photons, increasing the detection sensitivity.", "misconception": "Incorrectly thinking reverse bias narrows the depletion region"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Light emission occurs in forward-biased LEDs through electron-hole recombination. A photodiode under reverse bias detects light; it does not emit light.", "misconception": "Confusing photodiode (light detection) with LED (light emission)"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "In a Zener diode voltage regulator circuit, if the input voltage increases while the load resistance remains constant, then:", "explanation": "In a Zener regulator circuit, a series resistance is connected between the input and the Zener diode (which is in parallel with the load). When the input voltage increases, the Zener diode maintains a constant voltage across itself (equal to the Zener voltage). The excess voltage appears across the series resistance. To accommodate the increased input voltage at constant output voltage, the current through the series resistance increases. Since the load voltage (equal to Zener voltage) and load resistance remain constant, the load current stays the same, and the extra current flows through the Zener diode.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["zener-diode", "voltage-regulator", "series-resistance", "load-current"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode-06", "subtopic": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "topic_name": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "The voltage across the load remains constant and the current through the Zener diode increases", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "The voltage across the load increases proportionally", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "The current through the Zener diode decreases", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "The Zener diode stops conducting", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The entire purpose of a Zener regulator is to maintain a constant output voltage. The Zener diode clamps the voltage at V_Z regardless of input voltage variations (within design limits).", "misconception": "Not understanding the voltage-clamping action of a Zener diode"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "When input voltage increases, the total current from the source increases. Since load current is constant (constant V_Z and R_L), the excess current must flow through the Zener diode, so its current increases, not decreases.", "misconception": "Incorrectly analysing current distribution in a Zener regulator circuit"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The Zener diode continues to conduct in the breakdown region as long as the input voltage exceeds V_Z. An increase in input voltage keeps it well within the conducting range.", "misconception": "Confusing increased input voltage with loss of Zener conduction"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The colour of light emitted by an LED depends on:", "explanation": "The colour (wavelength) of light emitted by an LED is determined by the band gap energy (E_g) of the semiconductor material. When electrons recombine with holes across the junction, photons are emitted with energy approximately equal to the band gap: E = hc/lambda = E_g. Different semiconductor materials have different band gaps, producing different colours. For example, GaAs emits infrared, GaAsP emits red/yellow, and GaN emits blue light.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["LED", "band-gap", "wavelength", "semiconductor-materials"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode-07", "subtopic": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "topic_name": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "The forward current through the LED", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "The reverse bias voltage applied", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "The band gap of the semiconductor material used", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "The doping concentration of the semiconductor", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Increasing forward current increases the intensity (brightness) of the emitted light but does not change its colour. The wavelength is determined by the energy gap, not the current magnitude.", "misconception": "Confusing light intensity with light wavelength/colour"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "LEDs operate under forward bias, not reverse bias. Furthermore, the colour is an intrinsic property of the semiconductor material''s band gap, not of the applied voltage.", "misconception": "Incorrectly associating reverse bias with LED operation and colour"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "While doping affects conductivity and the Fermi level position, the emitted photon energy is primarily determined by the band gap energy of the host semiconductor material, not the doping concentration.", "misconception": "Confusing doping effects on conductivity with band gap energy determining emission wavelength"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "A solar cell is based on the photovoltaic effect. It works most efficiently when made from a semiconductor whose band gap is approximately:", "explanation": "A solar cell converts sunlight directly into electricity. The solar spectrum peaks in the visible region (around 1.5 eV photon energy). If the band gap is too small, the output voltage will be low and excess photon energy is wasted as heat. If the band gap is too large, most solar photons will not have enough energy to create electron-hole pairs. The optimal band gap for maximum efficiency (Shockley-Queisser limit) is approximately 1.5 eV, which corresponds to materials like GaAs (1.43 eV) and is close to CdTe (1.44 eV).", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["solar-cell", "photovoltaic-effect", "band-gap", "efficiency"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode-08", "subtopic": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "topic_name": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "0.1 eV", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "1.5 eV", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "5.0 eV", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "10.0 eV", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "A band gap of 0.1 eV is far too small. While most solar photons would be absorbed, the output voltage would be extremely low and most photon energy would be lost as heat, resulting in very poor efficiency.", "misconception": "Thinking a smaller band gap always means better solar cell performance"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "A 5.0 eV band gap corresponds to ultraviolet photon energies. Most visible and infrared solar photons (which carry the bulk of solar energy) would not have enough energy to generate electron-hole pairs.", "misconception": "Not relating the band gap to the solar spectrum distribution"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "10.0 eV is in the deep UV range. Essentially no solar photons reaching Earth''s surface have this energy, so such a material would produce virtually no photocurrent.", "misconception": "Not understanding the relationship between band gap and useful solar absorption"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "In a Zener diode regulator circuit, the Zener voltage is 6 V, the series resistance is 200 ohm, the load resistance is 1 kohm, and the unregulated input voltage varies from 10 V to 16 V. The minimum and maximum currents through the Zener diode are respectively:", "explanation": "The load current I_L = V_Z / R_L = 6/1000 = 6 mA (constant since V_Z and R_L are constant). At minimum input voltage (10 V): Total current I_S = (V_in - V_Z)/R_S = (10 - 6)/200 = 4/200 = 20 mA. Zener current I_Z = I_S - I_L = 20 - 6 = 14 mA. At maximum input voltage (16 V): I_S = (16 - 6)/200 = 10/200 = 50 mA. Zener current I_Z = 50 - 6 = 44 mA. Therefore, minimum I_Z = 14 mA and maximum I_Z = 44 mA.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["zener-diode", "voltage-regulator", "numerical", "series-resistance", "current-calculation"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode-09", "subtopic": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "topic_name": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "6 mA and 20 mA", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "20 mA and 50 mA", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "10 mA and 40 mA", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "14 mA and 44 mA", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "6 mA is the load current, not the Zener current. The Zener current is the difference between the total series current and the load current: I_Z = I_S - I_L.", "misconception": "Confusing load current with Zener diode current"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "20 mA and 50 mA are the total currents through the series resistance at 10 V and 16 V inputs respectively. You must subtract the load current (6 mA) to get the Zener current.", "misconception": "Forgetting to subtract the load current from the total series current"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Check the calculation: I_S(min) = (10-6)/200 = 20 mA, not 16 mA. The Zener current is 20 - 6 = 14 mA, not 10 mA.", "misconception": "Arithmetic error in computing the series current"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "In a full-wave rectifier circuit using a centre-tapped transformer, the peak voltage across each half of the secondary winding is V_m. If the diodes are ideal, the peak inverse voltage (PIV) that each diode must withstand is:", "explanation": "In a centre-tapped full-wave rectifier, when one diode (say D1) is conducting, the full voltage of that half-secondary (V_m) appears across the load. The non-conducting diode (D2) has its cathode at +V_m (the output voltage across the load) and its anode at -V_m (the voltage of the other half-secondary, which is in the opposite phase). Therefore, the reverse voltage across the non-conducting diode is V_m + V_m = 2V_m. This is the peak inverse voltage each diode must withstand.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["full-wave-rectifier", "peak-inverse-voltage", "centre-tapped-transformer", "diode-rating"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode-10", "subtopic": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "topic_name": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "V_m / 2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "V_m", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "2V_m", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "4V_m", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "V_m/2 is much too low. The non-conducting diode sees the entire voltage across the full secondary winding (both halves), which sums to 2V_m.", "misconception": "Incorrectly dividing the voltage instead of summing across both halves"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "V_m is the PIV for a half-wave rectifier. In a centre-tapped full-wave rectifier, the non-conducting diode has its anode at -V_m and cathode at +V_m, so PIV = 2V_m.", "misconception": "Confusing the PIV of a half-wave rectifier with that of a full-wave rectifier"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "4V_m is not correct for any standard rectifier configuration. For a centre-tapped full-wave rectifier, PIV = 2V_m exactly.", "misconception": "Incorrectly doubling the PIV value"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "An LED is fabricated from a semiconductor with a band gap of 2.0 eV. The wavelength of light emitted by this LED is approximately: (Given: h = 6.63 x 10⁻³⁴ J·s, c = 3 x 10⁸ m/s, 1 eV = 1.6 x 10⁻¹⁹ J)", "explanation": "The photon emitted during electron-hole recombination has energy approximately equal to the band gap: E = E_g = 2.0 eV. Using E = hc/λ, we get λ = hc/E = (6.63 x 10⁻³⁴ x 3 x 10⁸) / (2.0 x 1.6 x 10⁻¹⁹) = (19.89 x 10⁻²⁶) / (3.2 x 10⁻¹⁹) = 6.22 x 10⁻⁷ m = 6220 angstrom = 620 nm. This wavelength corresponds to orange-red light.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["LED", "band-gap", "wavelength-calculation", "photon-energy", "numerical"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode-11", "subtopic": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "topic_name": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "310 nm", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "620 nm", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "1240 nm", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "2480 nm", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "310 nm corresponds to a photon energy of about 4.0 eV (double the band gap). Ensure you divide hc by E_g, not multiply: λ = hc/E_g = 1240/2.0 = 620 nm.", "misconception": "Using 2E_g instead of E_g in the calculation"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "1240 nm would correspond to a band gap of 1.0 eV. You may have divided the band gap by 2 instead of using it directly. The formula is λ(nm) = 1240/E_g(eV).", "misconception": "Arithmetic error: using E_g/2 instead of E_g"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "2480 nm corresponds to a photon energy of only 0.5 eV. This would require a band gap four times smaller. Check: λ = 1240/2.0 = 620 nm.", "misconception": "Major calculation error in applying the energy-wavelength relation"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "In a rectifier circuit, a capacitor filter is connected across the load. The function of this filter capacitor is to:", "explanation": "The output of a rectifier is pulsating DC containing both a DC component and AC ripple. A capacitor connected in parallel (shunt) with the load charges up to the peak voltage during the conducting phase and discharges through the load during the non-conducting phase, filling in the gaps between pulses. This smooths out the ripple and produces a more nearly constant DC output voltage. The larger the capacitance and the load resistance, the smaller the ripple.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["filter-circuit", "capacitor", "ripple", "smoothing", "rectifier"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode-12", "subtopic": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "topic_name": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Reduce the ripple in the output and produce a smoother DC voltage", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Increase the output voltage above the peak AC voltage", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Convert DC back to AC for further processing", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Increase the output current of the rectifier", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "A filter capacitor charges up to the peak voltage but cannot exceed it (in a simple rectifier circuit). The output voltage remains at or below V_m, never above.", "misconception": "Thinking a capacitor can boost voltage beyond the peak value in a passive circuit"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Converting DC to AC requires an inverter circuit. A filter capacitor does the opposite: it removes the AC component from pulsating DC to produce smoother DC.", "misconception": "Reversing the role of a filter capacitor"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "A filter capacitor smooths voltage, but does not increase the average current delivered. In fact, it may reduce the average diode conduction time while maintaining a steadier voltage.", "misconception": "Confusing voltage smoothing with current amplification"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Assertion (A): A solar cell does not require an external bias to operate and can directly convert light energy into electrical energy.\nReason (R): The built-in electric field at the p-n junction of a solar cell separates the light-generated electron-hole pairs, creating a potential difference across the cell.", "explanation": "Both the assertion and reason are correct, and the reason correctly explains the assertion. A solar cell is an unbiased p-n junction device. When photons with energy greater than the band gap are absorbed near the junction, electron-hole pairs are generated. The built-in electric field in the depletion region sweeps electrons towards the n-side and holes towards the p-side, creating a photovoltage (open-circuit voltage). This is the photovoltaic effect. No external bias is needed because the junction''s own internal field performs the charge separation.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["solar-cell", "photovoltaic-effect", "built-in-field", "p-n-junction", "charge-separation"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode-13", "subtopic": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "topic_name": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The reason directly explains the assertion. The built-in electric field is the very mechanism by which the solar cell generates voltage without external bias. The reason is causally linked to the assertion.", "misconception": "Failing to see the direct causal connection between the built-in field and bias-free operation"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The reason is scientifically correct. The depletion region of any p-n junction has a built-in electric field that can separate charge carriers, and this is well-established physics.", "misconception": "Doubting the existence of the built-in electric field at the p-n junction"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The assertion is correct. Solar cells are widely used as bias-free energy conversion devices. They generate an EMF (typically 0.5-0.6 V for silicon) when illuminated without any external power supply.", "misconception": "Incorrectly thinking solar cells need external bias to function"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Assertion (A): The semiconductor materials used for fabricating LEDs must have a direct band gap.\nReason (R): In direct band gap semiconductors, the electron-hole recombination is predominantly radiative, emitting photons efficiently, whereas in indirect band gap semiconductors like silicon, recombination is mainly non-radiative.", "explanation": "Both the assertion and reason are correct, and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion. In a direct band gap semiconductor (like GaAs, GaN, GaAsP), the conduction band minimum and valence band maximum occur at the same value of crystal momentum (k). This allows direct electron-hole recombination with photon emission (radiative recombination) without needing a phonon for momentum conservation. In indirect band gap semiconductors (like Si, Ge), recombination requires a phonon to conserve momentum, making the process predominantly non-radiative (energy released as heat). Therefore, LEDs must use direct band gap materials for efficient light emission.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["LED", "direct-band-gap", "indirect-band-gap", "radiative-recombination", "GaAs", "silicon"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode-14", "subtopic": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "topic_name": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "bloom_level": "evaluate", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The reason directly explains why a direct band gap is necessary: efficient radiative recombination. This is the precise mechanism that makes direct band gap materials essential for LEDs, so R is the correct explanation of A.", "misconception": "Not recognising that radiative recombination efficiency is the reason for choosing direct band gap materials"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The reason is scientifically accurate. Direct band gap semiconductors do produce predominantly radiative recombination, and silicon (indirect band gap) is indeed a poor light emitter.", "misconception": "Doubting the distinction between radiative and non-radiative recombination in direct vs indirect gap materials"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The assertion is correct and well-established. All commercially successful LEDs use direct band gap semiconductors (GaAs, GaN, InGaN, GaP with nitrogen isoelectronic traps, etc.) for efficient light emission.", "misconception": "Incorrectly thinking LEDs can be made efficiently from any semiconductor"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Match the devices in Column I with their primary operating characteristics in Column II:\n\nColumn I:\nA. Half-wave rectifier\nB. Zener diode\nC. LED\nD. Photodiode\n\nColumn II:\n1. Operates in reverse bias; current depends on light intensity\n2. Forward biased p-n junction emitting light by electron-hole recombination\n3. Conducts only during one half of the AC input cycle\n4. Operates in reverse breakdown to maintain constant voltage", "explanation": "A half-wave rectifier uses a diode that conducts only during one half (positive or negative) of the AC input cycle (A-3). A Zener diode operates in the reverse breakdown region to maintain a constant voltage across the load (B-4). An LED is a forward-biased p-n junction that emits light when electrons and holes recombine across the junction (C-2). A photodiode operates in reverse bias, where the photocurrent varies with the intensity of incident light (D-1).", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["half-wave-rectifier", "zener-diode", "LED", "photodiode", "device-comparison"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode-15", "subtopic": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "topic_name": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A-4, B-3, C-2, D-1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "A-3, B-4, C-2, D-1", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "A-3, B-2, C-4, D-1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A-1, B-4, C-3, D-2", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "A-4 incorrectly pairs the half-wave rectifier with reverse breakdown operation. Reverse breakdown is the characteristic of a Zener diode, not a rectifier diode.", "misconception": "Confusing rectifier diode operation with Zener diode breakdown operation"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "B-2 incorrectly pairs the Zener diode with light emission. Light emission by recombination is the property of an LED. The Zener diode operates in reverse breakdown for voltage regulation (B-4).", "misconception": "Confusing Zener diode function with LED function"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "A-1 incorrectly states that a half-wave rectifier operates in reverse bias with light-dependent current. That describes a photodiode. A rectifier conducts during forward bias in one half-cycle.", "misconception": "Mixing up the fundamental operating principles of different diode devices"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Match the semiconductor materials in Column I with the typical colour/type of light emitted by LEDs made from them in Column II:\n\nColumn I:\nA. Gallium Arsenide (GaAs)\nB. Gallium Arsenide Phosphide (GaAsP)\nC. Gallium Nitride (GaN)\nD. Gallium Phosphide (GaP)\n\nColumn II:\n1. Blue light\n2. Red/Yellow light\n3. Green light\n4. Infrared radiation", "explanation": "GaAs has a band gap of about 1.4 eV, which corresponds to infrared radiation (A-4). GaAsP is a ternary alloy whose band gap can be tuned; it commonly emits red to yellow light depending on composition (B-2). GaN has a wide band gap of about 3.4 eV, producing blue light (C-1). GaP with appropriate dopants (like nitrogen) emits green light (D-3).", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["LED-materials", "GaAs", "GaAsP", "GaN", "GaP", "emission-wavelength"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode-16", "subtopic": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "topic_name": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A-1, B-2, C-4, D-3", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "A-2, B-4, C-1, D-3", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A-4, B-3, C-1, D-2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A-4, B-2, C-1, D-3", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "A-1 incorrectly assigns blue light to GaAs. GaAs has a band gap of only 1.4 eV, which corresponds to infrared radiation (not visible blue light). Blue LEDs require wide band gap materials like GaN.", "misconception": "Not knowing that GaAs emits in the infrared region due to its small band gap"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "A-2 and B-4 are swapped. GaAs (1.4 eV band gap) emits infrared, while GaAsP (tunable band gap around 1.9-2.0 eV) emits red/yellow visible light.", "misconception": "Confusing GaAs (infrared) with GaAsP (visible red/yellow)"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "B-3 and D-2 are swapped. GaAsP emits red/yellow light (not green), and GaP with nitrogen doping emits green light (not red/yellow).", "misconception": "Interchanging the emission colours of GaAsP and GaP"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "In a full-wave rectifier, both halves of the AC input cycle are utilised to produce output across the load, resulting in a higher average DC output voltage compared to a half-wave rectifier.", "explanation": "This statement is true. In a full-wave rectifier, both the positive and negative half-cycles of the input AC are rectified to produce unidirectional current through the load. The average DC output voltage of a full-wave rectifier is 2V_m/pi (approximately 0.636V_m), which is exactly double that of a half-wave rectifier (V_m/pi, approximately 0.318V_m). Therefore, a full-wave rectifier produces a higher average DC output voltage.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["full-wave-rectifier", "half-wave-rectifier", "average-voltage", "comparison"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode-17", "subtopic": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "topic_name": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The average DC output of a full-wave rectifier (2V_m/pi) is indeed double that of a half-wave rectifier (V_m/pi). This is because both half-cycles contribute to the output.", "misconception": "Not recognising that utilising both half-cycles doubles the average output"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This is a placeholder option and not a valid choice.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This is a placeholder option and not a valid choice.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "A photodiode is operated in forward bias to detect light, because forward bias increases the sensitivity to incident photons.", "explanation": "This statement is false. A photodiode is operated in reverse bias, not forward bias. Under reverse bias, the depletion region is widened, which increases the volume available for photon absorption and charge carrier generation. The strong electric field in the wide depletion region efficiently sweeps the photo-generated carriers, producing a measurable photocurrent that is proportional to light intensity. Forward bias would inject majority carriers, producing a large forward current that would overwhelm the small photocurrent signal.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["photodiode", "reverse-bias", "forward-bias", "light-detection"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode-18", "subtopic": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "topic_name": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Photodiodes are operated in reverse bias. Forward bias produces a large majority carrier current that masks the small photocurrent, making light detection impractical.", "misconception": "Confusing the bias condition of a photodiode with that of an LED"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This is a placeholder option and not a valid choice.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This is a placeholder option and not a valid choice.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "fill-in-blanks", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "A half-wave rectifier circuit uses an AC input of peak voltage 311 V (220 V rms) at 50 Hz. If the diode is ideal, the average DC output voltage is approximately _____ V. (Use V_dc = V_m / pi)", "explanation": "For a half-wave rectifier with an ideal diode, the average (mean) DC output voltage is given by V_dc = V_m / pi, where V_m is the peak voltage. Here V_m = 311 V. Therefore, V_dc = 311 / pi = 311 / 3.14 = 99 V (approximately). This is the standard formula for the average output of a half-wave rectifier.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["half-wave-rectifier", "average-voltage", "numerical", "peak-voltage"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode-19", "subtopic": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "topic_name": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "70", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "155", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "99", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "220", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "70 V would be approximately V_rms/pi. The correct formula uses the peak voltage, not the rms voltage: V_dc = V_m/pi = 311/3.14 = 99 V.", "misconception": "Using rms voltage instead of peak voltage in the average DC formula"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "155 V is approximately V_m/2 = 311/2. The average output of a half-wave rectifier is V_m/pi, not V_m/2.", "misconception": "Using V_m/2 instead of V_m/pi for average DC output"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "220 V is the rms value of the input AC, not the DC output. The half-wave rectified DC average is V_m/pi = 311/3.14 = 99 V.", "misconception": "Confusing the rms input voltage with the average DC output voltage"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "scenario-based", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "A student designs a Zener diode voltage regulator circuit to power a sensitive electronic device. The circuit uses a Zener diode with Zener voltage V_Z = 9 V, a series resistance R_S = 100 ohm, and a load resistance R_L = 300 ohm. The unregulated DC input voltage is 15 V.\n\nAssuming the Zener diode is ideal, the current flowing through the Zener diode is:", "explanation": "Since the Zener diode maintains V_Z = 9 V across the load, the load current is I_L = V_Z / R_L = 9 / 300 = 0.03 A = 30 mA. The current through the series resistance is I_S = (V_in - V_Z) / R_S = (15 - 9) / 100 = 6/100 = 0.06 A = 60 mA. By Kirchhoff''s current law at the junction: I_Z = I_S - I_L = 60 - 30 = 30 mA.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["zener-diode", "voltage-regulator", "numerical", "kirchhoff-current-law", "scenario"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-diode-20", "subtopic": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "topic_name": "Diode Applications (Rectifier, Zener, LED, Photodiode)", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "10 mA", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "20 mA", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "30 mA", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "60 mA", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "10 mA is incorrect. Recalculate: I_S = (15-9)/100 = 60 mA, I_L = 9/300 = 30 mA, so I_Z = 60 - 30 = 30 mA, not 10 mA.", "misconception": "Arithmetic error in current calculation"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "20 mA does not match the correct calculation. The series current is 60 mA and load current is 30 mA, giving I_Z = 30 mA.", "misconception": "Error in applying Kirchhoff''s current law at the junction"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "60 mA is the total current through the series resistance, not the Zener current. You must subtract the load current: I_Z = I_S - I_L = 60 - 30 = 30 mA.", "misconception": "Confusing total series current with Zener diode current"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "In a p-n junction diode under forward bias, the width of the depletion region:", "explanation": "When a p-n junction is forward biased (positive terminal connected to p-side), the applied voltage opposes the built-in potential barrier. This reduces the electric field in the depletion region, allowing majority carriers (holes from p-side and electrons from n-side) to diffuse across the junction. As a result, the depletion region width decreases. Conversely, under reverse bias, the depletion region widens because the applied voltage adds to the built-in potential.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["forward-bias", "depletion-region", "barrier-potential", "p-n-junction"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn-01", "subtopic": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "topic_name": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Decreases", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Increases", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Remains unchanged", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "First increases then decreases", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The depletion region increases under reverse bias, not forward bias. Forward bias reduces the barrier potential, narrowing the depletion region.", "misconception": "Confusing forward bias with reverse bias effects on the depletion region"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The depletion width is sensitive to applied voltage. An external bias always alters the effective potential across the junction, thereby changing the depletion width.", "misconception": "Assuming the depletion region is fixed regardless of external bias"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "There is no two-step behavior in forward bias. The depletion region monotonically decreases as forward voltage increases.", "misconception": "Incorrectly assuming a non-monotonic response to forward bias"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "In a p-type semiconductor, the majority charge carriers are:", "explanation": "A p-type semiconductor is formed by doping a pure (intrinsic) semiconductor like silicon with a trivalent impurity (e.g., boron, aluminium, gallium, indium). Each trivalent atom accepts an electron from a neighbouring silicon atom, creating a hole. Therefore, holes become the majority carriers and electrons remain the minority carriers in a p-type semiconductor.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["p-type-semiconductor", "majority-carriers", "holes", "trivalent-doping"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn-02", "subtopic": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "topic_name": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Electrons", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Holes", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "Protons", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Neutrons", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Electrons are the majority carriers in an n-type semiconductor, not in p-type. The ''p'' in p-type stands for positive (holes).", "misconception": "Confusing n-type and p-type majority carriers"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Protons are subatomic particles bound in the nucleus. They do not act as charge carriers in semiconductors.", "misconception": "Confusing mobile charge carriers in a crystal with nuclear particles"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Neutrons are electrically neutral nuclear particles. They cannot serve as charge carriers in any material.", "misconception": "Confusing charge carriers with nuclear constituents"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "The barrier potential of a silicon p-n junction diode at room temperature is approximately:", "explanation": "The barrier potential (also called built-in potential or contact potential) depends on the semiconductor material. For silicon (Si) at room temperature, the barrier potential is approximately 0.7 V. For germanium (Ge), it is approximately 0.3 V. This potential arises due to the diffusion of majority carriers across the junction during its formation, creating an electric field in the depletion region.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["barrier-potential", "silicon", "built-in-potential", "p-n-junction"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn-03", "subtopic": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "topic_name": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "0.1 V", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "0.3 V", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "0.7 V", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "1.5 V", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "0.1 V is too low for any standard semiconductor junction. Even germanium has a barrier potential of about 0.3 V.", "misconception": "Underestimating the barrier potential of semiconductor junctions"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "0.3 V is the barrier potential for a germanium diode, not a silicon diode. Silicon has a wider band gap and hence a higher barrier potential.", "misconception": "Confusing silicon barrier potential with germanium barrier potential"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "1.5 V is far too high for a single p-n junction. This value is closer to the voltage of a dry cell battery, not a diode barrier potential.", "misconception": "Overestimating the built-in potential of a silicon junction"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The energy band gap of silicon at room temperature is approximately:", "explanation": "The energy band gap (forbidden gap) of silicon at room temperature is approximately 1.1 eV. For germanium, it is about 0.67 eV. The band gap determines many electrical and optical properties of a semiconductor. Materials with a band gap of 0 eV are conductors, those with a small gap (< 3 eV) are semiconductors, and those with a large gap (> 3 eV) are insulators.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["energy-band-gap", "silicon", "forbidden-gap", "semiconductor"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn-04", "subtopic": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "topic_name": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "0.01 eV", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "0.67 eV", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "5.5 eV", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "1.1 eV", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "0.01 eV is far too small and would make the material behave almost like a conductor at room temperature.", "misconception": "Confusing the band gap of semiconductors with metals which have overlapping bands"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "0.67 eV is the band gap of germanium, not silicon. Silicon has a wider band gap than germanium.", "misconception": "Confusing the band gap values of silicon and germanium"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "5.5 eV is the band gap of diamond, which is an insulator. Semiconductors have band gaps typically between 0.5 eV and 3 eV.", "misconception": "Confusing semiconductor band gap with insulator band gap"}]}}]'::jsonb, 'deploy-2026-03-05-b10');

SELECT insert_batch_questions('[{"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "In the V-I characteristics of a p-n junction diode, the forward current increases sharply after the applied voltage exceeds:", "explanation": "In the forward-biased V-I characteristics, the current is negligible until the applied voltage overcomes the barrier potential (also called the knee voltage or cut-in voltage). For silicon, this is approximately 0.7 V and for germanium approximately 0.3 V. Beyond this threshold, the current increases approximately exponentially with voltage, as described by the Shockley diode equation: I = I₀(e^(eV/kT) − 1).", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["V-I-characteristics", "knee-voltage", "cut-in-voltage", "forward-bias", "silicon-diode"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn-05", "subtopic": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "topic_name": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "The barrier potential (knee voltage) of the diode", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "The breakdown voltage of the diode", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Zero applied voltage", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "The reverse saturation current value", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "Breakdown voltage is a reverse-bias phenomenon where large reverse current flows. The sharp rise in forward current occurs at the knee voltage, not at breakdown.", "misconception": "Confusing forward knee voltage with reverse breakdown voltage"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "At zero applied voltage, the junction is in thermal equilibrium and no net current flows. The sharp rise occurs only after the barrier potential is overcome.", "misconception": "Assuming current rises sharply from zero voltage"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The reverse saturation current I₀ is a tiny current in reverse bias. It is not a voltage threshold that triggers forward current increase.", "misconception": "Confusing reverse saturation current with forward bias voltage threshold"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "When a p-n junction is formed, the diffusion current flows:", "explanation": "When a p-n junction is formed, majority carriers on each side tend to diffuse across the junction due to the concentration gradient. Holes from the p-side (higher concentration) diffuse to the n-side, and electrons from the n-side (higher concentration) diffuse to the p-side. The conventional current (direction of positive charge movement) due to this diffusion is from the p-side to the n-side. This diffusion exposes immobile ions in the depletion region, creating an electric field that drives a drift current in the opposite direction. At equilibrium, the diffusion and drift currents balance each other.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["diffusion-current", "p-n-junction-formation", "majority-carriers", "concentration-gradient"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn-06", "subtopic": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "topic_name": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "From n-side to p-side", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "From p-side to n-side", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "Equally in both directions", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Only within the depletion region", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "The drift current (due to the built-in electric field) flows from n-side to p-side. The diffusion current flows in the opposite direction: p-side to n-side.", "misconception": "Confusing the direction of diffusion current with drift current"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Diffusion is directional—majority carriers move from high to low concentration. Holes diffuse p→n and electrons n→p, both contributing to conventional current from p to n.", "misconception": "Assuming diffusion current has no net direction"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Diffusion current involves majority carriers crossing the junction. It is not confined to the depletion region; carriers diffuse from the bulk regions toward and across the junction.", "misconception": "Incorrectly restricting diffusion current to the depletion region only"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "In a reverse-biased p-n junction, the current is mainly due to:", "explanation": "In reverse bias, the applied voltage increases the barrier potential, preventing majority carriers from crossing the junction. However, minority carriers (electrons in the p-side and holes in the n-side) that are thermally generated near the depletion region are swept across by the electric field, producing a small reverse saturation current. This current is nearly independent of the applied reverse voltage and depends primarily on temperature, as it originates from thermally generated electron-hole pairs.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["reverse-bias", "minority-carriers", "reverse-saturation-current", "thermal-generation"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn-07", "subtopic": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "topic_name": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Majority carriers from both sides", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Only holes from the n-side", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Minority carriers drifting across the junction", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "Free electrons from the external circuit entering the depletion region", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Majority carriers are repelled by the increased barrier in reverse bias. They cannot cross the junction; hence they do not contribute to reverse current.", "misconception": "Assuming majority carriers can overcome the enhanced barrier in reverse bias"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "While holes in the n-side (minority carriers) do contribute, electrons in the p-side (also minority carriers) contribute equally. The current is due to all minority carriers, not just holes.", "misconception": "Considering only one type of minority carrier in reverse bias current"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "External circuit electrons enter at the terminal contacts, not directly into the depletion region. The reverse current through the junction is due to internally generated minority carriers.", "misconception": "Confusing internal junction current with external circuit electron flow"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The depletion region in a p-n junction is formed due to:", "explanation": "When a p-n junction is formed, electrons from the n-side and holes from the p-side diffuse across the junction due to their concentration gradients. As they recombine near the junction, they leave behind uncompensated immobile ions: negative acceptor ions (NA⁻) on the p-side and positive donor ions (ND⁺) on the n-side. This region of immobile ions, devoid of free charge carriers, is the depletion region. The immobile ions create an internal electric field directed from n to p, which opposes further diffusion.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["depletion-region", "immobile-ions", "diffusion", "recombination", "p-n-junction-formation"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn-08", "subtopic": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "topic_name": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Accumulation of free electrons and holes at the junction", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "External voltage applied across the junction", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Thermal generation of electron-hole pairs at the junction", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Diffusion and recombination of majority carriers leaving behind immobile ions", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "The depletion region is characterized by the absence of free carriers, not their accumulation. Free carriers recombine and leave behind only immobile ions.", "misconception": "Thinking the depletion region has accumulated free carriers"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "The depletion region forms naturally during p-n junction fabrication without any external voltage. External voltage only modifies the width of the existing depletion region.", "misconception": "Assuming external voltage is needed to form the depletion region"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Thermal generation of electron-hole pairs occurs everywhere in the semiconductor. It does not cause the formation of the depletion region; diffusion and recombination of majority carriers does.", "misconception": "Confusing thermal generation with the diffusion process that creates the depletion region"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The dynamic (AC) resistance of a forward-biased silicon diode at room temperature carrying a current of 10 mA is approximately:", "explanation": "The dynamic resistance of a diode is given by r = kT/(eI) = V_T/I, where V_T is the thermal voltage. At room temperature (T ≈ 300 K), V_T = kT/e ≈ 26 mV. For a forward current I = 10 mA: r = 26 mV / 10 mA = 2.6 Ω. This is the small-signal resistance that determines how the diode responds to small AC signals superimposed on the DC bias.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["dynamic-resistance", "thermal-voltage", "forward-bias", "AC-resistance"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn-09", "subtopic": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "topic_name": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "0.26 Ω", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "2.6 Ω", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "26 Ω", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "260 Ω", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "0.26 Ω would result if you used 2.6 mV instead of 26 mV for the thermal voltage. At room temperature V_T ≈ 26 mV, giving r = 26/10 = 2.6 Ω.", "misconception": "Using an incorrect value for the thermal voltage"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "26 Ω would result from using I = 1 mA instead of 10 mA. Check: r = 26 mV / 10 mA = 2.6 Ω.", "misconception": "Using 1 mA instead of the given 10 mA current"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "260 Ω would result from using I = 0.1 mA. With I = 10 mA: r = V_T/I = 26 mV / 10 mA = 2.6 Ω.", "misconception": "Incorrect conversion of current units leading to a much higher resistance"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "In an n-type semiconductor, the Fermi level lies:", "explanation": "In an n-type semiconductor, pentavalent donor impurities introduce additional energy levels (donor levels) just below the conduction band. Since donors provide extra electrons, the probability of finding electrons near the conduction band increases. The Fermi level, which represents the energy at which the probability of electron occupancy is 1/2, shifts upward from the middle of the band gap and lies closer to the conduction band. In a p-type semiconductor, the Fermi level shifts closer to the valence band.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["fermi-level", "n-type-semiconductor", "donor-levels", "energy-bands"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn-10", "subtopic": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "topic_name": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Closer to the conduction band", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Closer to the valence band", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Exactly at the centre of the forbidden gap", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Inside the valence band", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The Fermi level lies closer to the valence band in a p-type semiconductor, not in an n-type. For n-type, excess electrons shift the Fermi level toward the conduction band.", "misconception": "Confusing the Fermi level position in n-type and p-type semiconductors"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The Fermi level lies at the centre of the band gap only in an intrinsic (pure) semiconductor. Doping shifts the Fermi level toward the band of the majority carrier.", "misconception": "Applying intrinsic semiconductor properties to extrinsic semiconductors"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The Fermi level inside the valence band would imply a heavily p-doped semiconductor or a metal. In an n-type semiconductor, it shifts toward the conduction band.", "misconception": "Incorrectly placing the Fermi level of an n-type semiconductor in the valence band"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "A silicon p-n junction diode has a reverse saturation current of 10 μA at 27°C. If the diode is forward biased with a voltage of 0.6 V, the forward current is approximately (given: e = 1.6 × 10⁻¹⁹ C, k = 1.38 × 10⁻²³ J/K):", "explanation": "Using the Shockley diode equation: I = I₀(e^(eV/kT) − 1). At T = 27°C = 300 K, the thermal voltage V_T = kT/e = (1.38 × 10⁻²³ × 300)/(1.6 × 10⁻¹⁹) ≈ 0.026 V = 26 mV. The exponent eV/kT = 0.6/0.026 ≈ 23.08. So e^(23.08) ≈ 1.06 × 10¹⁰. Since this is much greater than 1, I ≈ I₀ × e^(eV/kT) = 10 × 10⁻⁶ × 1.06 × 10¹⁰ ≈ 1.06 × 10⁵ μA ≈ 106 mA ≈ 0.1 A. Among the options, approximately 0.1 A is the closest.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["shockley-equation", "forward-current", "thermal-voltage", "exponential-dependence"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn-11", "subtopic": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "topic_name": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "10 μA", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "10 mA", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Approximately 0.1 A", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "Approximately 10 A", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "10 μA is the reverse saturation current I₀. The forward current at 0.6 V is many orders of magnitude higher due to the exponential factor e^(eV/kT) ≈ 10¹⁰.", "misconception": "Forgetting the exponential amplification of current in forward bias"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "10 mA would require the exponential factor to be about 10³, which corresponds to V ≈ 0.18 V. At 0.6 V, the factor is approximately 10¹⁰, giving a much larger current.", "misconception": "Underestimating the exponential growth of diode current with voltage"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "10 A would require the exponential factor to be about 10⁶ times the correct value. The calculation gives e^(23) ≈ 10¹⁰, so I ≈ 10⁻⁵ × 10¹⁰ = 10⁵ μA ≈ 0.1 A.", "misconception": "Errors in computing the exponential or unit conversion"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "In a p-n junction, the depletion region extends more into the lightly doped side. If the doping concentration on the n-side is 10 times that on the p-side, the ratio of the depletion width on the p-side (xₚ) to that on the n-side (xₙ) is:", "explanation": "The charge neutrality condition for the depletion region requires that the total charge on each side be equal: NA × xₚ = ND × xₙ, where NA and ND are the acceptor and donor concentrations, and xₚ and xₙ are the depletion widths on the p-side and n-side respectively. Given ND = 10 NA, we get: NA × xₚ = 10 NA × xₙ, which simplifies to xₚ/xₙ = 10. The depletion region extends 10 times more into the lightly doped p-side.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["depletion-width", "doping-concentration", "charge-neutrality", "asymmetric-junction"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn-12", "subtopic": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "topic_name": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "1 : 10", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "1 : 1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "5 : 1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "10 : 1", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "1:10 implies the depletion region extends more into the heavily doped n-side, which is the opposite of what happens. The depletion region extends more into the lightly doped side.", "misconception": "Reversing the relationship between doping concentration and depletion width"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "A 1:1 ratio would mean equal extension on both sides, which only occurs when both sides have equal doping. With unequal doping, the depletion region is asymmetric.", "misconception": "Assuming equal depletion widths regardless of doping asymmetry"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "5:1 does not satisfy the charge neutrality condition NA × xₚ = ND × xₙ. With ND = 10 NA, the correct ratio is xₚ/xₙ = 10.", "misconception": "Incorrectly applying the charge neutrality condition or averaging the doping ratio"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Assertion (A): The reverse saturation current of a p-n junction diode increases with increase in temperature.\n\nReason (R): With increase in temperature, the generation of electron-hole pairs increases, which enhances the minority carrier concentration on both sides of the junction.", "explanation": "The Assertion is true: the reverse saturation current I₀ increases with temperature. I₀ depends on the minority carrier concentration, which is thermally generated. The Reason is also true: higher temperature provides more thermal energy, increasing the rate of electron-hole pair generation, thereby increasing minority carrier concentration. Since the reverse current is due to minority carriers drifting across the junction under the influence of the internal electric field, increased minority carriers directly increase I₀. The Reason correctly explains the Assertion.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["reverse-saturation-current", "temperature-dependence", "minority-carriers", "thermal-generation"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn-13", "subtopic": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "topic_name": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are true, but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is true but R is false", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is false but R is true", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The Reason directly addresses why reverse saturation current increases: more thermal generation means more minority carriers, which directly causes the increase in I₀. So R is indeed the correct explanation.", "misconception": "Failing to see the causal link between minority carrier generation and reverse saturation current"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The Reason is factually correct—thermal energy does increase electron-hole pair generation at higher temperatures. Both statements are true.", "misconception": "Incorrectly evaluating the truth of the Reason statement"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The Assertion is true—reverse saturation current is well known to increase roughly by a factor of 2 for every 10°C rise in temperature.", "misconception": "Incorrectly believing reverse saturation current is temperature-independent"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Assertion (A): In a p-n junction diode, the electric field in the depletion region is directed from the n-side to the p-side.\n\nReason (R): The depletion region on the n-side has exposed positive donor ions, and the depletion region on the p-side has exposed negative acceptor ions.", "explanation": "The Assertion is true: the built-in electric field in the depletion region points from the n-side (positive ions) to the p-side (negative ions). The Reason is also true: during junction formation, diffusion of majority carriers leaves behind immobile positive donor ions (ND⁺) on the n-side and negative acceptor ions (NA⁻) on the p-side. These immobile ions create a charge distribution that produces the electric field directed from the positive charges (n-side) to the negative charges (p-side). The Reason correctly explains the Assertion.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["electric-field", "depletion-region", "immobile-ions", "built-in-field", "donor-acceptor-ions"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn-14", "subtopic": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "topic_name": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are true, but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is true but R is false", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is false but R is true", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The Reason directly explains the origin of the electric field: positive ions on the n-side and negative ions on the p-side create an electric field pointing from n to p. This is exactly why the Assertion is true.", "misconception": "Not recognizing that the immobile ion distribution is the direct cause of the built-in electric field"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The Reason is factually correct. After diffusion and recombination, donors on the n-side lose their extra electrons (becoming ND⁺) and acceptors on the p-side gain electrons (becoming NA⁻).", "misconception": "Incorrectly believing that donor ions are negative or acceptor ions are positive"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The Assertion is correct. Electric field lines point from positive to negative charges, i.e., from the positively charged n-side of the depletion region to the negatively charged p-side.", "misconception": "Reversing the direction of the built-in electric field in the depletion region"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Match the following terms (Column I) with their correct descriptions (Column II):\n\nColumn I:\n(P) Intrinsic semiconductor\n(Q) n-type semiconductor\n(R) p-type semiconductor\n(S) Depletion region\n\nColumn II:\n(1) Region devoid of free charge carriers near the junction\n(2) Doped with pentavalent impurity; electrons are majority carriers\n(3) Pure semiconductor with equal electron and hole concentrations\n(4) Doped with trivalent impurity; holes are majority carriers", "explanation": "(P) Intrinsic semiconductor → (3): An intrinsic semiconductor is a pure semiconductor (e.g., pure Si or Ge) with no intentional doping. In it, electron concentration equals hole concentration (nₑ = nₕ = nᵢ). (Q) n-type semiconductor → (2): Doped with pentavalent impurities (P, As, Sb) that donate extra electrons, making electrons the majority carriers. (R) p-type semiconductor → (4): Doped with trivalent impurities (B, Al, Ga, In) that accept electrons creating holes, making holes the majority carriers. (S) Depletion region → (1): The narrow region near the p-n junction devoid of free mobile charge carriers, containing only immobile donor and acceptor ions.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["intrinsic-semiconductor", "n-type", "p-type", "depletion-region", "doping"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn-15", "subtopic": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "topic_name": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "P→3, Q→4, R→2, S→1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "P→3, Q→2, R→4, S→1", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "P→1, Q→2, R→4, S→3", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "P→3, Q→2, R→1, S→4", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This option swaps n-type and p-type descriptions. n-type is doped with pentavalent impurity (electrons majority), p-type with trivalent impurity (holes majority).", "misconception": "Confusing n-type and p-type doping and their majority carriers"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This option incorrectly matches intrinsic semiconductor with the depletion region description and vice versa. An intrinsic semiconductor is a pure semiconductor, not a depletion region.", "misconception": "Confusing intrinsic semiconductor with the depletion region concept"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This option matches p-type semiconductor with the depletion region description, which is incorrect. p-type semiconductor is doped with trivalent impurity.", "misconception": "Incorrectly associating p-type semiconductor with the depletion region"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Match the following bias conditions (Column I) with their effects on a p-n junction diode (Column II):\n\nColumn I:\n(P) Forward bias with V > V_knee\n(Q) Forward bias with V < V_knee\n(R) Reverse bias with V < V_breakdown\n(S) Reverse bias with V ≥ V_breakdown\n\nColumn II:\n(1) Very small current flows; depletion region widens; only minority carriers drift across\n(2) Large current flows exponentially; depletion region is very narrow; low dynamic resistance\n(3) Negligible current flows; depletion region slightly reduced but barrier not fully overcome\n(4) Sudden large reverse current flows; can permanently damage the diode if uncontrolled", "explanation": "(P) Forward bias with V > V_knee → (2): Once the applied forward voltage exceeds the knee voltage (~0.7 V for Si), the barrier is effectively overcome, and current increases exponentially. The depletion region becomes very narrow and dynamic resistance is low. (Q) Forward bias with V < V_knee → (3): Below the knee voltage, the applied voltage partially reduces the barrier but not enough for significant current flow. Only a negligible current flows. (R) Reverse bias with V < V_breakdown → (1): In normal reverse bias, the depletion region widens, and only a small reverse saturation current due to minority carriers flows. (S) Reverse bias with V ≥ V_breakdown → (4): At breakdown voltage, either Zener effect or avalanche multiplication causes a sudden dramatic increase in reverse current, which can damage the diode if not limited by an external resistance.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["forward-bias", "reverse-bias", "knee-voltage", "breakdown-voltage", "V-I-characteristics"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn-16", "subtopic": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "topic_name": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "P→2, Q→1, R→3, S→4", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "P→4, Q→3, R→1, S→2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "P→2, Q→3, R→1, S→4", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "P→3, Q→2, R→4, S→1", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This swaps Q and R. Forward bias below knee voltage gives negligible current (not minority carrier drift), while reverse bias below breakdown gives small current due to minority carriers.", "misconception": "Confusing the behavior of sub-threshold forward bias with normal reverse bias"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "This assigns breakdown behavior to forward bias above knee voltage, which is incorrect. Forward bias above knee voltage gives large exponential current, not breakdown.", "misconception": "Confusing forward conduction with reverse breakdown"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This completely reverses the forward and reverse bias effects. Forward bias above knee gives large current, not negligible current.", "misconception": "Fundamentally reversing forward and reverse bias behaviors"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "In a p-n junction at thermal equilibrium (no external bias), the net current through the junction is zero because the diffusion current is exactly balanced by the drift current.", "explanation": "This statement is TRUE. When a p-n junction is formed and reaches thermal equilibrium (no external voltage applied), majority carriers diffuse across the junction due to concentration gradients, creating a diffusion current. Simultaneously, the electric field in the depletion region (created by immobile ions) sweeps minority carriers across, producing a drift current in the opposite direction. At equilibrium, these two currents are exactly equal and opposite, resulting in zero net current through the junction. This is the fundamental equilibrium condition of a p-n junction.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["thermal-equilibrium", "diffusion-current", "drift-current", "zero-net-current", "p-n-junction"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn-17", "subtopic": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "topic_name": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The statement is correct. At thermal equilibrium, diffusion and drift currents must balance (Kirchhoff''s current law for zero external voltage). A non-zero net current would violate thermodynamic equilibrium.", "misconception": "Thinking that a built-in potential drives a continuous net current at equilibrium"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "In a p-type semiconductor, the majority carriers are electrons and the minority carriers are holes.", "explanation": "This statement is FALSE. In a p-type semiconductor, the majority carriers are holes (created by trivalent acceptor impurities such as B, Al, Ga, In) and the minority carriers are electrons. The statement has the carriers reversed. The ''p'' in p-type stands for positive, referring to the positive holes that are the majority carriers. Electrons, being thermally generated in smaller numbers, are the minority carriers in p-type material.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["p-type-semiconductor", "majority-carriers", "minority-carriers", "holes", "electrons"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn-18", "subtopic": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "topic_name": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "The statement reverses the carrier types. In p-type semiconductors, holes are majority carriers and electrons are minority carriers, not the other way around.", "misconception": "Confusing majority and minority carriers in p-type semiconductors"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "fill-in-blanks", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "When a p-n junction diode is reverse biased beyond a critical voltage called the ________ voltage, a sudden and large increase in current occurs due to either Zener effect or avalanche multiplication.", "explanation": "The correct answer is ''breakdown'' voltage. When the reverse bias voltage applied across a p-n junction diode exceeds a certain critical value called the breakdown voltage, the reverse current increases dramatically. This can occur through two mechanisms: (1) Zener breakdown — occurs in heavily doped, narrow-junction diodes (typically V_breakdown < 6 V) where the intense electric field directly ionizes atoms by pulling electrons from covalent bonds (quantum mechanical tunneling); (2) Avalanche breakdown — occurs in lightly doped, wider-junction diodes (typically V_breakdown > 6 V) where accelerated carriers gain enough kinetic energy to knock out additional carriers through impact ionization, creating a chain reaction.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["breakdown-voltage", "zener-breakdown", "avalanche-breakdown", "reverse-bias"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn-19", "subtopic": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "topic_name": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "knee", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "threshold", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "breakdown", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "saturation", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Knee voltage (cut-in voltage) refers to the forward bias voltage at which current begins to rise sharply. The question describes a reverse-bias phenomenon.", "misconception": "Confusing forward knee voltage with reverse breakdown voltage"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "Threshold voltage is a general term often used in transistors (e.g., MOSFETs). In the context of a diode''s reverse bias large current surge, the correct term is breakdown voltage.", "misconception": "Using the wrong technical term for the reverse bias critical voltage"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Saturation refers to the small, nearly constant reverse current before breakdown, not the voltage at which the sudden current surge occurs.", "misconception": "Confusing reverse saturation current region with the breakdown phenomenon"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "scenario-based", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "A student sets up a circuit to study the V-I characteristics of a silicon p-n junction diode. She connects a variable DC power supply, a series resistance of 1 kΩ, and an ammeter in series with the diode, and a voltmeter in parallel with the diode. When the applied EMF from the power supply is 5 V in forward bias configuration, the voltmeter across the diode reads 0.7 V. What is the current through the diode as indicated by the ammeter?", "explanation": "In the forward-biased circuit, the total EMF (5 V) is distributed across the series resistance and the diode. The voltage across the series resistance R is: V_R = EMF − V_diode = 5 V − 0.7 V = 4.3 V. Using Ohm''s law, the current through the circuit (and hence through the diode, since they are in series) is: I = V_R / R = 4.3 V / 1000 Ω = 4.3 × 10⁻³ A = 4.3 mA. The series resistance serves as a current-limiting resistor to protect the diode from excessive current.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["forward-bias-circuit", "series-resistance", "ohms-law", "V-I-characteristics", "current-calculation"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-pn-20", "subtopic": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "topic_name": "p-n Junction Diode and Characteristics", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "5.0 mA", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "0.7 mA", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "5.7 mA", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "4.3 mA", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "5.0 mA would result from using I = EMF/R = 5/1000, ignoring the 0.7 V drop across the diode. The voltage across the resistor is EMF − V_diode = 4.3 V, not 5 V.", "misconception": "Neglecting the voltage drop across the forward-biased diode"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "0.7 mA would result from using I = V_diode/R = 0.7/1000. The current is determined by the voltage across the resistor, not the voltage across the diode.", "misconception": "Using the diode voltage instead of the resistor voltage to calculate current"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "5.7 mA would result from incorrectly adding EMF and V_diode (5 + 0.7 = 5.7 V) and dividing by R. The correct voltage across R is EMF − V_diode = 4.3 V.", "misconception": "Adding instead of subtracting the diode voltage drop from the supply EMF"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-transistor", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "In an npn transistor, the majority charge carriers in the emitter region are:", "explanation": "In an npn transistor, the emitter is an n-type semiconductor. In n-type semiconductors, electrons are the majority charge carriers because the material is doped with pentavalent (donor) impurities that provide extra electrons to the conduction band.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["npn-transistor", "majority-carriers", "emitter", "n-type"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-transistor-01", "subtopic": "Transistor, Logic Gates, and Amplifiers", "topic_name": "Transistor, Logic Gates, and Amplifiers", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Holes", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Protons", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Electrons", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "Positive ions", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Holes are the majority carriers in p-type semiconductors. In an npn transistor, the emitter is n-type, so electrons are the majority carriers.", "misconception": "Confusing carrier types in n-type and p-type semiconductors"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "Protons are bound within the nucleus and do not participate in electrical conduction in semiconductors.", "misconception": "Confusing charge carriers with nuclear particles"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Positive ions in the crystal lattice are immobile and do not act as charge carriers for current flow.", "misconception": "Confusing fixed lattice ions with mobile charge carriers"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-transistor", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "In a transistor, the base region is:", "explanation": "The base region of a transistor is intentionally made very thin (of the order of a few micrometres) and is lightly doped compared to the emitter. This ensures that most charge carriers injected from the emitter pass through the base and reach the collector, rather than recombining in the base region. This is essential for effective transistor action.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["transistor-structure", "base-region", "doping", "thin-base"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-transistor-02", "subtopic": "Transistor, Logic Gates, and Amplifiers", "topic_name": "Transistor, Logic Gates, and Amplifiers", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Thick and heavily doped", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Thin and lightly doped", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "Thick and lightly doped", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Thin and heavily doped", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "If the base were thick and heavily doped, most carriers from the emitter would recombine in the base, and very little current would reach the collector. Transistor action would fail.", "misconception": "Not understanding the design requirement for efficient carrier transfer"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Although the base is lightly doped, it must also be thin. A thick base would cause excessive recombination of carriers before they reach the collector.", "misconception": "Partially correct but ignoring the thickness requirement"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Heavy doping of the base would increase recombination of minority carriers, drastically reducing the collector current and current gain.", "misconception": "Confusing the doping requirement of base with that of emitter"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-transistor", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "The output of a NAND gate is LOW (0) only when:", "explanation": "A NAND gate is the complement of an AND gate. The AND gate gives output 1 only when all inputs are 1. Therefore, the NAND gate gives output 0 only when all inputs are HIGH (1). For all other input combinations, the NAND gate output is HIGH (1). The Boolean expression for a two-input NAND gate is Y = (A.B)'' = A'' + B'' (by De Morgan''s theorem).", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["NAND-gate", "truth-table", "logic-gates"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-transistor-03", "subtopic": "Transistor, Logic Gates, and Amplifiers", "topic_name": "Transistor, Logic Gates, and Amplifiers", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "All inputs are LOW", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Any one input is HIGH", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Any one input is LOW", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "All inputs are HIGH", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "When all inputs are LOW, the AND operation gives 0, and its complement (NAND) gives 1. So the output is HIGH, not LOW.", "misconception": "Confusing NAND gate behaviour with NOR gate behaviour"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "Having any one input HIGH does not determine the NAND output to be LOW. NAND output is LOW only when ALL inputs are HIGH.", "misconception": "Confusing NAND with OR complement logic"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "When any input is LOW, the AND operation gives 0, and the NAND output is 1 (HIGH). This describes when the output is HIGH, not LOW.", "misconception": "Describing the condition for HIGH output instead of LOW"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electronic-devices", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-semi-transistor", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "Which logic gate is called a universal gate?", "explanation": "NAND and NOR gates are called universal gates because any Boolean function or any other logic gate (AND, OR, NOT) can be realised using only NAND gates or only NOR gates. This makes them fundamental building blocks in digital electronics. AND, OR, and NOT gates alone are not universal because each cannot generate all other gates by itself.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["universal-gate", "NAND-gate", "NOR-gate", "logic-gates"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-semi-transistor-04", "subtopic": "Transistor, Logic Gates, and Amplifiers", "topic_name": "Transistor, Logic Gates, and Amplifiers", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "NAND and NOR", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "AND and OR", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "NOT and AND", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "OR and NOT", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "AND and OR gates cannot produce a NOT function by themselves. You cannot invert a signal using only AND or OR gates, so they are not universal.", "misconception": "Thinking basic gates are universal because they are fundamental"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "NOT and AND together can realise all functions (they form a functionally complete set), but individually neither is called a universal gate. The term ''universal gate'' specifically refers to NAND and NOR.", "misconception": "Confusing functional completeness of a set with the universal gate concept"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "OR and NOT together can also form a complete set, but they are not individually called universal gates. Only NAND and NOR each individually can produce all other gates.", "misconception": "Confusing a complete set of gates with individually universal gates"}]}}]'::jsonb, 'deploy-2026-03-05-b10');

